deck_excerpt: The most thematically accurate Dartz deck I could come up with. I hope it suits your tastes.
deck_description:
This deck aims to closely resemble the anime version of Dartz's deck while maintaining functionality. Here's a breakdown of how each card contributes to the deck's strategy:

  1. Ancient Jar: This is your generic normal monster used to summon Shunoros. Its thematic fit with Orichalcos Kyutora and flavor text make it a suitable choice.

  2. Revival Golem / Gigantes Combo: This combo serves as a thematic fit resembling Orichalcos Gigas. You can easily send Revival Golem to the graveyard with Rock Bombardment, then special summon it to defend you. When destroyed, you can banish it to summon Gigantes, offering constant defense and disruption effects.

  3. Element Doom: While not identical to Orichalcos Malevolence, Element Doom serves as a thematic replacement with its fitting appearance and potential usefulness, especially with Orichalcos boosting its ATK.

  4. Scapeghost: Chosen for its thematic fit, Scapeghost offers excellent stall options, especially with Supply Squad. With The Seal of Orichalcos on the field, you can put tokens in attack mode to lock your opponent from attacking you.

  5. Witch of the Black Forest: Included as a searcher to improve consistency, Witch was chosen for its thematic fit despite initial reluctance.

  6. Divine Serpent Geh: Limited to one due to its potential risks, Geh serves as an ace in the sleeve to summon after Shunoros or in dire situations.

  7. The Cauldron of the Old Man: Reflecting Dartz's life point gain, this card accumulates life points or can be used for a burn effect to finish off opponents.

  8. Decisive Battle of Golgonda: While not thematically fitting, this card offers crucial protection for boss monsters and backrow, making it essential for the deck's functionality.

  9. United We Stand: Two copies are included to boost Shunoros or any other monster as needed, with the option to recycle them later with Jar of Avarice.

Overall, each card in the deck (including the ones not mentioned) aims to mimic the functions of Dartz's cards, creating a thematic and functional deck that closely resembles his anime deck.

deck_excerpt: OTK with Ancient Gear in Masterduel's 2024 Legend Anthology Event!
deck_description:
Deploy gigantic war machines with ridiculously high attack and obliterate your opponents lifepoints in one turn!

This deck is specifically made for Masterduel's 2024 Legend Anthology Event. The lower power level of the strategies in Legend Anthology means that blinding second with Ancient Gear is an easy pushover allowing you to obliterate any gamestate, board and monster your opponent manages to put up!

There is no in-depth guide for this deck, since Legend Anthology lasts for a couple days anyways. For Ancient Gear, you basically amass enough resources to allow you to fuse into Chaos Ancient Gear Giant which is your main win condition. You can also summon two level 10 monsters for a rank 10 train OTK.

GLHF Duelists!


Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

Hey everyone, Archfiend Guy here, bringing you a Yubel deck! Yubel is awesome, fun to play, and really strong. Full video deck guide is linked for anyone interested.

Starters:

  • Samsara D Lotus
  • Nightmare Throne
  • Dark Beckoning Beast / Opening of the Spirit Gates

One Card Combo example (Nightmare Throne):

  1. Activate Nightmare Throne, add Samsara
  2. Summon Samsara, activate effect, summon Spirit of Yubel, set Nightmare Pain
  3. Activate Nightmare Pain, pop Spirit, add Squirmer
  4. CL1 Spirit, CL2 Throne, search Terror Incarnate, summon, summon Yubel
  5. Special Summon Squirmer, link it and Terror into Soul King Yama, add Sharvara
  6. Sharvara pop Yubel, summon itself, float into Terror
  7. Link Sharvara + Yama into Soul of Rage, set Escape of the Unchained
  8. Activate Squirmer, summon Yubel
  9. End Phase, Yubel tribute Terror, float into Ultimate Nightmare. Samsara Special Summon itself
  10. Their turn: Activate Escape as a disrupt, popping Soul and their card. CL1 Yama, CL2 Soul (add Spirit, revive Soul). At THIS point, you can opt to pop Yubel and float into Terror. Then, you can use Samsara's disrupt on Terror to float into both Ultimate Nightmare and Spirit of Yubel off Throne (setting Eternal Favourite for the clapback).
  11. Finally, Soul of Rage effect into S:P for 3 disruptions. A total of 5-6 disruptions off of one card.'

Two Card Combo Example (Dark Beckoning Beast + Nightmare Throne)

  1. Activate Throne, add Lotus
  2. Summon Beast, add Gates, activate Gates, add Beast
  3. Summon Lotus, activate effect into Spirit of Yubel, set Pain
  4. Activate Gates, discard Beast, summon Beast
  5. Overlay both Beasts into Djinn Buster (5th summon, eliminate Nibiru threat)
  6. Flip Pain, pop Spirit, search Squirmer, float off Spirit into Yubel, float off Throne into Terror
  7. Special Summon Squirmer, link Squirmer + Terror into Soul King Yama, add Sharvara
  8. Sharvara pop Yubel, summon itself, float into Terror
  9. Link Sharvara + Yama into Soul of Rage, set Escape of the Unchained
  10. Activate Squirmer, summon Yubel
  11. End Phase, Yubel tribute Terror, float into Ultimate Nightmare. Samsara Special Summon itself
  12. Same disruptions as above, but with Djinn Buster

There's way more than just these two. But points to consider:

If you have Opening of the Spirit Gates on the field and a level 10 (e.g. Spirit of Yubel), then set Pain and pop it with Sharvara before using it. You can then activate Gates to bring Pain back into your hand. Activate Pain, go off.

Eternal Favourite cannot super poly the moment you flip the card up because of game mechanics. Also, you cannot activate Spirit of Yubel's effect off of it UNLESS it is a chain link 2 or higher. So always chain Favourite if you're doing this.

The optimal Nightmare Throne floats are off Spirit or Terror Incarnate so that you float both ways, letting you go into Yubel/Spirit (starting the floating all over again) and Ultimate Nightmare/Terror to float up.

Quick OTK:

  1. Summon Lotus, effect into Spirit, add Pain
  2. Activate Throne, search Yubel
  3. Pain pops Spirit, add Geist Grinder Golem, float into Yubel, float into Terror Incarnate
  4. Geist effect target Yubel, summon both. 9000 Damage + 2000 with Gustav Max

Finally, for a bonus 2 card 8 interrupt combo that uses Promethean Princess:

INTERRUPTIONS

  1. Soul of Rage (S:P = 3 interrupts)
  2. Escape
  3. Samsara
  4. Spirit of Yubel in hand
  5. Promethean Princess pop
  6. Amblowhale pop from GY

RECURSION

  1. Duelittle recycles Sharvara

FLOATS

  1. Throne into whatever (best trigger = Terror Incarnate)
  2. Spirit into Yubel

CLAPBACK

  1. Eternal Favourite

Use Soul of Rage 1st into S:P, when Yama pops Amblowhale, revive Soul of Rage to make Escape a double pop.

COMBO LINE

  1. Summon Beckoning, add Gates
  2. Activate Throne, add Samsara
  3. Activate Gates, add Beckoning
  4. Summon Samsara, activate, summon Spirit
  5. Activate Spirit, set Pain
  6. Activate Nightmare Pain, use effect, pop Spirit, search Squirmer
  7. Spirit float into Yubel
  8. Link Beckoning + Yubel into Yama, search Sharvara
  9. Use Gates, discard Beckoning, summon Yubel
  10. Sharvara target Yubel, summon, float into Terror Incarnate
  11. Link Sharvara and Yama into Promethean Princess
  12. Sharvara set Escape
  13. Promethean revive Sharvara
  14. Link Promethean + Sharvara into Duelittle Chimera
  15. Activate Squirmer, pop Terror
  16. Activate Yama, Terror and Throne, summon Spirit + Ultimate * Nightmare + Sharvara (or anything), pop Escape, summon Sarama
  17. Activate Sarama, set Escape, pop Spirit, float into Yubel
  18. Link Squirmer + Ultimate Nightmare into Yama
  19. Link Sharvara + Yama into Soul of Rage
  20. Banish Squirmer from GY to summon Yubel
  21. Link Yubel + Sarama into I:P Masquerena
  22. End Phase, activate Samsara to summon itself, then pop Yubel or tribute the Samsara

Their turn

  1. Use Soul of Rage into S:P for 3 interrupts
  2. Use Promethean target Chimera, summon itself, CL1 Yama (revive Spirit of Yubel), CL2 I:P into Amblowhale, CL3 Chimera target Sarama. Yama pop Amblowhale to revive Soul of Rage. Spirit eff set Eternal Favourite.
  3. Escape pop Soul of Rage, recycle Spirit of Yubel into hand, Amblow eff to pop
  4. Samsara pop Spirit, Spirit float (+Throne float)

Have fun everyone! Keen to hear your thoughts

deck_excerpt: Number 43 FTK ft. Royal Magical Library + Numbers Eveil
deck_description:
Hello and welcome to another guide, where the aim is to FTK your opponent with Number 43. Rather than bot setup, this one can be considered as creative one. Let's get into action!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Play your spells to fill your GY while drawing your combo pieces. Then, XYZ Summon Dugares and pass it to your opponent with "Shien's Spy".

2) Activate "Soul Absorption". Then, activate "Numbers Eveil" to bring forth Number 43 with other XYZ monsters you have.

3) Although not shown, Lizardraw could have been destroyed to draw a card, provided there is another Performapal monster on other Pendulum Zone. With two free spaces you have, you could set "That Wacky Magic!" and play "Contract with the Void" to fill your GY with more spells. Then, activate "That Wacky Magic!" afterwards to banish all of your spells to gain lots of LP.

4) The amount you gained should be far more than your opponent's LP, even if you have played 3 x Upstart Goblin. Simply pull the trigger with Number 43 and win the game!

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Wonder Wand" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Into The Void" can be either found within "The Infinite Void" or "Life Force Control System" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "Soul Absorption" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 30 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" + "Numbers Eveil" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR and 30 UR!

- "Performapal Monkeyboard" can be found within "The Bizarre Playing Board" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 240 SR and 60 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!
Joshua Schmidt's Bystial Runick

deck_excerpt: Judgment Dragon, Punishment Dragon, Enlightenment Dragon
deck_description: Still crafting and testing the new Lightsworns released. Focused on revamping ace monsters Judgment Dragon and Punishment Dragon, and using boss monster Enlightenment Dragon as often as I can (with its Synchro Minerva combo as well as the Cross-sheep combo as extender). Great disruption improvements compared to the old Lightsworns, especially with omni-negate Lightsworn Aegis (2 is enough; sometimes 1 is even okay already). Side Deck mainly consists of suggested cards that you can also put to use (I am not focused on tweaking to adapt or disrupt opponents in between duels for this one, these are suggestions for your build). I also preferred the Bystials over the Tearlaments support since I can aim for the Level 10 Synchros and the recycling capability of Branded Regained instead of the engine milling and free fusion provided by the Tearlaments. Also, I have loved Lightsworns ever since I discovered them in 2009, and I've been using them since. I almost quit Yu-Gi-Oh! when they released almost useless cards post-Twilightsworns. I am glad Punishment Dragon is viable now, and a purer Lightsworn deck in general. Peace!

deck_excerpt: Obliterate your opponent's board and OTK! Going first? Set up an Cyberdark UNAFFECTED 5000ATK towers monster!
deck_description:
Cyber Dragon has long been a pet deck of mine since forever - I mean, who doesn't like giant serpentine killer robot dragons?! That's such a cool concept for a Yugioh deck! Ever since I've watched GX in my childhood, the machine archetypes of that Yugioh generation have captured my heart - including the Cyber Dragons. However, this archetype has (so far) never reached competitive viability and has always been a mediocre rogue deck.

At least we can play it decently in 2024's Legend Anthology! Obliterate your opponent's board and OTK! This deck is specifically made for Masterduel's 2024 Legend Anthology Event.

Going first? Set up an Cyberdark UNAFFECTED 5000ATK towers monster!

I know that the combo guide to Cyberdarj Cyberdragon is kind of lengthy, but I'm too lazy to create a combo guide for this casual deck. To fuse into your Cyberdark monster, basically amass 5 Cyberdark monsters in your GY and fuse them all together for your Cyberdarkness Dragon.

As for the Cyberdragon side of the deck, check out my latest Cyberdragon guide. It's a bit dated, but it should feature similar strategy, gameplay and combos to this deck.

deck_description: Get a calculator and keep dividing by 2.

The Format known as Yugi-Kaiba is the earliest meta in the TCG, consisting of only Legend of Blue-Eyes and the two Yugi and Kaiba Starter Decks.

The Limited card pool means most decks are comprised of largely the same cards, with a lot of them being auto includes. There's no banlist, but there's a limited list, which are all auto-includes, except for the 5 Exodia pieces. There's also a semi-limited list, which is only Swords and Card Destruction, the former an auto-include at 2, and the latter is a staple also usually at two.

Historic decks aside, Control represents the overwhelming majority of the meta, particularly with Soul Exchange, and with a mill variant relying on Card Destruction, and some Burn variants.

This list was made by compiling the decklists at the YGO Format Library, going through the top event decks and seeing what cards where used and how often. Some cards did not make the list, but should still be considered, and to note that these are not the exact card ratios you'd use, particularly Side-Board/Main-Board wise.

This list is meant as a starting point, these cards are used in the OVERWHELMING MAJORITY of the decks, usually in these quantities. The mainboard trap cards are used in every single deck at full playset and so are most of the cards mainboarded.

Sometimes not used as a full playset are Soul Exchange, Summoned Skull, Neo, Battle Ox, and Wall of Illusion. Everything else mainboarded and/or used as a full playset is invariably in these ratios distributed between main and side board.

Most decks will at least consider running 1 De-Spell, rarely 2, never 3. The Wicked Worm Beast and Trap Master are common deck at varying ratios. Aqua Madoor and Ultimate Offering are also usually run.

Of note is that even Aggro and Turbo decks will use most of these cards, with just some minor changes to account for their particular strategies (notably, Dragon Turbo will swap in Blue-Eyes and dragon support cards), so anyone wanting to get into the format work their way from here with a rock-solid foundation.

deck_excerpt: Performapal Odd-Eyes ft. Superheavy Samurai + Bystial
deck_description:
(Disclaimer: Apologies in advance if I did major mistakes while facing against Branded, as I'm still trying to do my best to learn. Branded Lost was surely painful to deal with.)

Greetings! I'm so excited to share with you all, my first serious rogue deck: Performapal Odd-Eyes. Here, SHS (Superheavy Samurai) utilizes Pendulum Tuners for Synchron plays while Bystials act as means of hand-trap and tutoring Odd-Eyes or Bystial cards because you can't use any Spell or Trap cards in SHS package. It's really shocking how all three are in harmony. So, let's begin!

 

(That was a wild ride for sure!)

 

Gameplan

- Generally, Pendulum decks have no linear path. Depending on what you start with, your endboard may be different but try to aim placing Apollo as Link Monster and Baronne / Borreload / Dragster as Synchron Monster. One or two Synchron shall be enough. If possible, you can also Fusion Summon Vortex to finalize your negate city, where you need to block your opponent from doing anything mischievous.

- Your primary goal in the beginning should be utilizing Odd-Eyes Arc Pendulum Dragon in Pendulum Zone, so that you can cheat out monsters. If you have Fusion Summoned Vortex and Vortex is in GY, always target Vortex to shuffle your opponent's Attack Positioned monster and have Spell/Trap/Monster negator ready.

- It all starts with Link 2 monsters. Have two bodies present onboard to either make Electrumite or Beyond. Using Odd-Eyes Arc Pendulum Dragon (Pendulum Effect) + Bystials + Performapal Odd-Eyes Butler may help you in that regard.

- I'll try to do my best with explaining all three packages in different categories:

 

1) Performapal Odd-Eyes: While they are initially different archetypes, they have mutual relations. Some of members from this package are really scary if not unchecked...

  • For example, if you have Normal/Special Summoned "Performapal Celestial Magician" while having Synchron Monsters, you can activate Celestial to not let your opponent activate any monster effects. If you have any Pendulum Monster present, Celestial can tutor any Pendulum Monster. Also, trivia; If you have Pendulum Synchron monster (Symphonic Warrior Rockks), Celestial checks both conditions that were previously explained.
  • Here are cards from this package, where you can place them in Pendulum Zone...
    • Performapal Gentrude: Either pop Gentrude on Pendulum Zone or as Monster card via Electrumite / Baronne to place any "Performapal" Pendulum monster except Gentrude later on.
    • Performapal Odd-Eyes Butler: If popped with Electrumite / Baronne as Monster card, Butler can be placed in Pendulum Zone.
    • Performapal Odd-Eyes Valet: If popped with Electrumite / Baronne as Monster card, Valet can be placed in Pendulum Zone.
    • Performapal Ladyange: If Ladyange was sent to GY, either via Odd-Eyes Valet or Odd-Eyes Seer, you can place her in Pendulum Zone.
  • Here are cards from this package, where you can cheat out Extra Deck monsters...
    • Odd-Eyes Arc Pendulum Dragon: Only from Pendulum Zone, you can revive Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon from your GY, if you have properly Fusion Summoned Vortex.
    • Performapal Celestial Magician: Only from Pendulum Zone, if one of your Extra Deck monsters but Links were killed first time, you can pop Celestial to revive said monster. It means that if your Extra Deck monster was in your GY beforehand, you can't use Celestial again.
    • Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon: Only from Pendulum Zone, if there are any Extra Deck Dragon monsters except Links in your GY, you can revive said monster. Candidates are as follows...
      • Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon
      • Bystial Dis Pater
  • Here are your tutors from this package...
    • Performapal Skullcrobat Joker: Normal Summon to find "Performapal" or "Odd-Eyes" or "Magician" monsters except Joker.
    • Odd-Eyes Pendulum Dragon: Only from Pendulum Zone, pop it to find any Pendulum Monster with <= 1500 ATK.
    • Performapal Monkeyboard: Only from Pendulum Zone, you can find Level 4- "Performapal" monster.
    • Performapal Celestial Magician: If Normal/Special Summoned while having another Pendulum Monster, you can find any Pendulum Monster during your End Phase.
    • Performapal Pendulum Sorcerer: If Special Summoned, pop up to two of your cards to find "Performapal" monsters but Sorcerer.
    • Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon: Discard this fella and pay 500 LP to find either Arc Pendulum or Pendulum Dragon, Level 7 Dragon Pendulum Monsters. On a side note, if you have Normal/Special Summoned "Oafdragon Magician", you can fetch Revolution Dragon from your GY to your hand.
    • Oafdragon Magician: As explained previously, you can either find "Magician" or "Odd-Eyes" monsters from your GY to fetch them into your hand. Mostly used for Revolution Dragon but you can also find any targets coming from Odd-Eyes Valet or Odd-Eyes Seer.
  • Here is an example of starter: If you have Odd-Eyes Seer in hand...
    1. Normal Summon Skullcrobat Joker
    2. Find Revolution Dragon
    3. Use Revolution Dragon to find Arc Pendulum Dragon
    4. Place Arc Pendulum Dragon and Odd-Eyes Seer to Pendulum Zones
    5. Use Odd-Eyes Seer to pop Seer and fetch Revolution Dragon into your hand
    6. Use Arc Pendulum Dragon to pull out "Odd-Eyes" monster from your Hand or Deck or GY...
      • Don't bother with Hand unless you are forced.
      • Best GY target is Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon.
      • Best Deck target is Odd-Eyes Valet, followed by Odd-Eyes Dissolver. Valet can send Ladyange to GY, where you can place her into Pendulum Zone. Alternatively, Valet can send Butler to GY and you can pop either "Performapal" or "Odd-Eyes" Monster card you have to Special Summon Butler. If possible, detonate Pendulum Zone to not lose any bodies onboard. As for Dissolver, you can use Dissolver and any redundant Pendulum card on Pendulum Zone to Fusion Summon Vortex. Don't bother with Pendulum Effect of Dissolver, it's not worth doing it.
  • Via Odd-Eyes Seer, if Pendulum Summoned, do the following...
    • Place as Defense >>> Send Butler to GY for extra body or Ladyange for Pendulum Scale
    • Place as Attack >>> Banish Odd-Eyes Seer >>> Revive Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon or Performapal Pendulum Sorcerer

 

If you have come this far, congratulations. You have finally crossed the biggest hurdle. Rest shall be easy. If I have missed anything in "Performapal Odd-Eyes" section, let me know. Onwards to next one...

 

2) Superheavy Samurai (SHS)

  • At the cost of using no Spells or Traps, you can use Wakaushi to Special Summon it from Pendulum Zone while placing Big Benkei.
  • Your priority should be using Wakaushi with Level 6 monsters (Bystials + Odd-Eyes Seer + Oafdragon + Monkeyboard) to start the journey with Baronne and whatnot.
  • Feel free to do the math and explore other Synchro monsters. Even though Guitariss isn't a SHS monster, it's another Pendulum Tuner, where you can use Level 4 monsters to form Dragster / Pegasus / Rockks.

 

3) Bystial

  • These monsters can either give you extra bodies or act as hand-traps.
  • As Level 6 monsters, if combined with Wakaushi, can lead into Level 10 Synchro plays.
  • Since Bystials like to banish monsters, you can go extreme with cards such as Punisher + Omega + Chaos Angel + Chengying + Dis-Pater.
  • Lubellion can tutor any Bystial monster you like while Magnamhut can tutor any Dragon Monster, including Odd-Eyes Dragons, during the End Phase of a turn.
  • Baldrake and Druiswurm can act as means of disruption. Use them wisely.

 

That's all for this guide. If you have any questions or suggestions or feedback, feel free to write here. Most of all, have fun with playing Master Duel!

Gimmick Puppet decks are pretty fun and quite o.p once you learn it. Some combo's and information about this deck and how to use it.
I find this deck is better to use on the 2nd turn, if you have to go first try and stall until your next turn. 

-Mecha Phantom Beast combo: Mecha Phantom Beast can special summon a token, you can use the Mecha Phantom Beast and the token to link summon Gimmick Puppet Chimera Doll, use Chimera's effect to discard Gimmick Puppet Dreary Doll, then special summon a Gimmick monster from your hand.
Multiple possible scenario's after this combo.

1-if you have Gimmick Puppet Shadow Feeler you can put that in defence position and use it's ability to stall for another turn provided you have spells and traps in your hand or set that you can use on there next turn that can protect it.

2-if you have Gimmick Puppet Bisque Doll and another gimmick puppet monster in your hand, discard 1 gimmick monster using Bisque Doll's effect, special summon in defence, use gimmick puppet dreary dolls effect in the graveyard banishing the discarded monster you just put in the graveyard, special summon dreary doll in defence, then you can special summon XYZ monsters.

3-if you have Humpty Dumpty and Baby Terror, special summon Humpty and use its effect to special summon Terror Baby, XYZ summon into Gigantes Doll or Dreadnought Dreadnoid depending on your situation. If you oppenent has monsters on the field, best to summon Gigantes, steal 2 of there monsters, tribute Gigantes and make there levels 8 and XYZ summon either Gimmick Puppet of Strings or Giant Grinder. If they have spells/traps and a weak monster on the field use dreadnaught to XYZ summon Galaxy Destroyer and wipe there spells and traps.

-Gimmick Puppet Des Troy/Humpty Dumpty/Dreary Doll combo: Normal Summon Des Troy, use its effect and destroy Des Troy to special summon 2 gimmick puppets monsters from your hand, special summon Dreary Doll and Humpty Dumpty, if you have another gimmick monster in your hand, use humpty dumptys effect to special summon that as well, then link summon Chimera using Dreary Doll and Humpty as the materials, add Shadow Feeler to your hand, special summon it, use dreary dolls effect in the graveyard, banish Des Troy and special summon Dreary Doll, XYZ summon into Giant Grinder or Puppet of Strings.
If you used Humpty Dumpty effect to special summon another Gimmick monster, special summon Terror Baby or another Humpty Dumpty, XYZ summon Gigantes, steal your opponents monster, use Gigantes effect make them level 8 and XYZ summon another Gimmick monster.

(Monster Card Tips)
-Gearspring Spirit is a easy to card to special summon when 1 machine monster is in the graveyard, good to get Rank 8 XYZ cards out.
-Gimmick Puppet Twilight Joker is a safe card, just keep it your hand when a Gimmick monster gets destroyed by battle, can work with perform Puppet.
-Gimmick Puppet Des Troy can easily special summon 2 Gimmick monsters from your hand.
-Gimmick Puppet Shadow Feeler is a great stall card, especially if they're being lazy and don't read it's effect.
-Dreary Doll/Bisque Doll/Magnet Doll are easy special summon cards to get out Rank 8 XYZ Monsters. Use Bisque Doll's effect, discard Dreary Doll and special summon Bisque, then use Magnet Dolls effect and special summon Magnet Doll, if they have no monsters on there field you can use Gearspring Spirit instead. Use Junk Puppet/Monster Reborn and Special summon Dreary from the graveyard, then link summon Chimera using Dreary Doll and Magnet Doll as link materials, use Chimera effect, add shadow feeler to hand, special summon it then use dreary effect in graveyard, discard Magnet Doll and special summon Dreary Doll for XYZ summons.

(Spell/Trap tips)
-Rank Up Spells Good for Puppet of Strings or Giant Grinder, easy board wipes against special summoned monsters.
-Dragon Nails Protects from Card effects that destroy the equiped monster plus a boost in attack, to get that otk wipe when you can get 2 XYZ's on one turn and have Chimera out.
-Perform Puppet good to banish cards then summon the banished cards
-Machine Duplication great for getting out Dreary Doll or Humpty Dumpty
-Puppet Parade is amazing for mass summoning when your oppenent has a lot of monsters on the field.
-Condolence Puppet good for sending Dreary Doll to the Graveyard to get a easy special summon and it can protect a XYZ card on the field if its in the graveyard.

(XYZ Tips)
-Number 15: Gimmick Puppet Giant Grinder is good when your oppenent has special summoned monsters on the field, summon it in defence. Use the effect twice and destroy 2 special summoned monsters on your oppenents field, if you have a ranked up spell use it after you use the effects, then XYZ summon Giant Hunter use the effect and destroy another Monster or spell/trap.
-Number 40: Gimmick Puppet of Strings is a good board wipe if you have a ranked up spell card, use the effect and place string counters on your opponents monsters, use the rank up spell and XYZ summon Gimmick Puppet of Dark Strings, dark strings effect will activate destroying your opponents monsters with string counters. (This all puts string counters on your monsters if you have any on the field, destroying them as well. So be careful when you do this)
-Gimmick Puppet Gigantes Doll is great for stealing your oppenents monsters and using them to XYZ summon for your extra deck
-Number 27: Dreadnought Dreadnoid is good when you can destroy the oppenents monster, then use its effect to XYZ summon Superdimensional Robot Galaxy Destroyer
-Number 68: Sanaphond The Sky Prison is great for stalling. You can discard a card, then until your oppenents next turn it cant be destroyed by card effects, it also gains 200 atk/def for each monster in both graveyards, which works great with this deck.
-Number 88: Gimmick Puppet of Leo is a good panic button for the oppenent. You can win the duel if you discard 3 XYZ materials this card has and you have no spell or trap cards on your field. Good end game card as well, especially if its in your graveyard, you have a rank up spell, junk puppet/monster reborn in your hand or perform puppet active on the field and you have 2000 life points or less. Use can use Junk Puppet/monster reborn to special it from your graveyard, use rank up on it, special summon Disaster Leo, detach the XYZ material, inflict 1000 damage and end your turn and win the duel.
-Number c88: Gimmick Puppet Disaster Leo Better for end games and you have Gimmick Puppet of Leo in your graveyard.

(Side Deck)
-United we Stand gets you more attack than Dragon Nails, replace Dragon Nails for this card if you want more damage.
-Machina Cannon you can special summon by discarding 1 or more machine monsters from your hand (discard Dreary Doll) you can replace Twilight Joker or Twin Twisters for this card.
-Des Troy and Mecha Phantom Beast you can replace with Twilight Joker.

This is my TCG Dark Magician Deck. I'm running a budget friendly version for obvious reasons. 

 

 

Here, you can see I run the infamous "iffy" tech card (according to the DM community), Palladium Oracle Mahad. What a lot of DM players don't realize (skill issue tbh) is that Mahad is a level 7 Light monster. Magician's Rod is a level 3 Dark monster. This means that if you can manage to Special Summon Mahad to your field with your Rod out (giggity), then you can make a Chaos Angel that's unaffected by your opponent's activated monster effects AND protects ALL of your monsters on the board from being destroyed by battle (WOW). Knowing that you can do this with PURE Dark Magician (who would've thought) and not have to run some cheesy engine that takes up deck space (and significantly lowers your pride & self-respect) truly is a feeling like no other. Not to mention, a lot of the time, you can use him as an extra body for Link/XYZ plays (BLS/Big Eye), a Dark monster beat stick (because of his passive effect), cost for Timaeus, dump fodder for Souls in addition to the +1 he provides for Soul Servant. Nothing screams "Giga Chad" more than making Pot of Greed look obselete. Besides, more often than not, he'll stay in the Main Deck and if you manage to open him, use him for fusion with DM or put him back on top of the deck with Illusion of Chaos. Let's not forget he can also do everything mentioned IN ADDITION to just being a MUCH stronger version of Magikuriboh with his 3rd effect. He can also be Special Summoned from the GY via Master of Chaos's effect and tributed to non-target banish ALL of your opponent's monsters from the field (his utility is so versatile). Dark Magician players tend to look everywhere for support except for their own archetype (crazy, isn't it) which is why Mahad is so slept on.

 

 

Honorable mention goes out to Ebon High. I prefer High over Illusion simply because High can play Traps and Quick-Plays from hand during your opponent's turn. Let's say opponent activates a card to pop one of the floodgates in the back row; upon the resolution of that effect, I can discard 1 material and activate another INSTANTLY. Then, if he gets sent to the GY for whatever reason, I can Special Summon a Dark Spellcaster body from deck and non-target pop 1 card on field. That Special Summon can be ANY of the Dark Spellcaster monsters in your deck (of ANY LEVEL as long as they can be Special/Normal Summoned). Once upon a time for me, that choice was most often going to be DMoC (but because of the 4 bricks I already run and absolutely having to Normal Summon him, he's just too much of a liability...super fun to do though). Unfortunately, because I RARELY ever have a chance to make Ebon High and flex these big brain plays, I just choose to go with Big Eye because his materials are super generic (not that it actually matters in a Level 7 Spellcaster deck tbh) and his effect is just a free Snatch n Steal x2 with no LP gain for opponent (unga bunga gimme your body to make more monsters).

 

 

Dragostapellia, Borrelsword, Linkmail, and the Knightmare cards are just generic filler cards that I use to fill up Extra Deck space. I mean, they're alright (insert that one meme). I don't need Phoenix because I choose to run the SEARCHABLE in-archetype Harpie's Feather Duster (because you can tech it with Illusion of Chaos for essentially a free search+add to hand). It sure beats running 5-7 EXTRA cards that don't synergize with Dark Magician like Talent/Thrust just to search Harpie's (I swear that idea makes no sense to me...just play DM Pure and use the space for other cards) and its 2nd effect is not worth it. Chaos Angel does it way better. Unicorn is meh at best (really mid card for 3 bodies tbh). I probably won't even need Dragoon either. I typically do pretty well without it in my deck on Master Duel. However, I'm open to testing him out and seeing if he'll be worth adding to my deck when I do finally obtain a copy or two.

 

 

Floodgates are what I'll be mainly running in my deck due to how much it will (typically) stop my opponent. Meta-contending decks tend to have multiple attributes/types and need to summon more than twice to have a solid board. If I end up learning that my match-up can play around any of them, then I can easily just Special Summon Magicians' Souls and send them to the GY for a free Pot of Greed (synergy...gotta love it). However, because I don't currently have access to Souls, I won't be running any floodgates (seldom Summon Limit because DM can easily set up with 2 summons) because I'll pretty much have no way to get them off my field when I need to cook. Also, because I opt to run Eternal Soul in my deck, my opponent will have more incentive to go for the floodgate(s) which means Eternal Soul is potentially safe (at least long enough for me to make Dragon Knight).

 

 

You might also notice the lack of the staple hand traps/interruptions such as Ash, Nib, Droll or anything in likeness. That's not how I intend to play the deck containing the ultimate wizard in terms of attack and defense. I have a bone to pick with modern YGO and how it's played. The farthest I will go down the hand trap rabbit hole is Imperm and Evenly (if we even consider that a hand trap).

 

 

Eclipse & Moon are self-explanitory. So are Widowmaker, Dark Ruler, the Runick Spells and Spellbound (they're just flat-out "no's" to your opponent).

 

 

When I'm able to obtain more of the cards I typically run (see my Master Duel Dark Magician deck on my profile), I will most likely be swapping out some of the current cards you see with those.

 

 

I currently don't run a side deck because I don't have enough cards to make a fully fleshed out one nor do I truly think I'll need one. If I do end up making one, I'll add those cards to the decklist.

 

 

As for the other cards I plan on obtaining (list below), I'll get them when and if I'm in a position to do so. I wouldn't be running budget DM if I didn't have to. I'll remove each from the list once I obtain them. If you find yourself reading this, and end up meeting me somehow, I'm open to trading (or if you simply just want to hook me up, that'd be pretty sick too, but it's necessary).

 

 

 

 

Cards I Plan On Adding Eventually:

- 1x Chaos Angel

- 1x Guardian Chimera

- 3x Magicians' Souls

- 1x Number 11: Big Eye

- 1x Accesscode Talker

- 1x Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon

- 1-3x Skill Drain

- 1-3x Rivalry of Warlords

- 1-3x Gozen Match

- 1-3x Summon Limit

- 3x Evenly Matched

- 3x Infinite Impermanence

- 3x Preperation of Rites (waiting on that to come in mail)

- 1x Artemis (waiting on that to come in mail)

- 1x Magician Salvation (waiting on that to come in mail)

- 1x Millennium-Eyes Restrict

deck_excerpt: Trades are tough, but honest work.
deck_description:
Iron Chain Repairman revives Iron Chain Coil to make level 7 synchros. Send Iron Chain Coil to the graveyard with Scrap Recycler to set up Iron Chain Repairman plays. Because this deck can summon Ancient Fairy Dragon, I added the field spells Geartown and Black Garden to take full advantage of the dragon's effects. Geartown summons the powerful Ancient Gear Gadjiltron Dragon when destroyed and Black Garden's revival effect can be used with Summoner Monk, Breaker the Magical Warrior, and Iron Chain Repairman.

Some Tips

Two Treacherous Trap Holes are used because the benefits of drawing 1 outweigh the chance of drawing another in the same match. Summoner Monk can summon Snipe Hunter, Thunder King Rai-Oh, and Kycoo the Ghost Destroyer from the deck. Ancient Gear Engineer dismantles backrow and is searchable with Geartown and Giant Rat. Forbidden Chalice is a flexible card that can negate the opponent's monster effects or boost your own monsters' attack. In this deck, Forbidden Chalice most notably counters Caius the Shadow Monarch and Vanity's Fiend, whose boosted attacks are still lower than Ancient Gear Gadjiltron Dragon's stats.

Voiceless but with boardbraeaker and blowout cards.

With the maindecking of Super Poly, I decided to tailor the extra to be more tool box style with more specific Super Poly targets. Big eye and Barronne can be substituted for Mereologic Aggregator and Malong, respectively, as these cards have effects when used for Ultimate Slayer. Barrone is great in simplified game states. Dyna Mondo helps you to recycle materials if you have already used Radiance, but I don't have enough data to decide on whether I want the second copy. 

If you decide to run a link climbing package with the use of charmers and selene, you could cut the Goddess, either the Linkuriboh or Almiraj, and the Draco-Equiste/@ignister or both if you want to run more than 1 charmer. IF you do decide to go this route, you would probably cut Fenrir for Veiler as Selene requires you to special the spell caster in denese position. The trade-off to this is that it plays into TTT. Going the link climbing package also lets you trade out the Ulti Slayers for something like Evenly Matched

You could easily go into the Nadir package with the way extra deck is designed. I would just add an extra Garura to keep your Super Poly plays alive while being able to draw a card.

Still experimenting with some combination of Fenrir/Nib/Droll. Fenrir is definitlely the better card when going first; however, Nibiru is defenitely a better card to be drawn in case you lose the die roll. Nib can be used if the ritual spell is hard drawn and you have no access to Safira immediately since the spell does require a LIGHT attribute tribute(s). Fenrir going second is also a trigger for Promethian Princess so it can be sided out for either Duster/ Lightning Storm/ ECon depending on the matchup. I think TTT is too good to not be in the main this format and wanted it in any capacity. It gives you infomation on your oppenents hand if you do get drolled going first and is a draw 2 in case your Prosperity or Pre-Prep is Ashed. You could just cut it completely and play the 3rd copy of Pre-Prep to keep the deck at a clean 40. 

Econ also triggers Diviner's effect to get access to Lo, since it tributes for cost even if Diviner is negated and dodges destruction. Lightning Storms can be swapped out for Cosmic Cyclones if you are seeing more Centurion and Floodgates. Anti-Spell checks a lot of the spell heavy decks right now and can just outright win you a game.

Hi, Grayewick the Fusionist here, back after a year or so of being missing and not having posted anything.

But yeah, here's pure T.G.s. Yeah, I know it's not a Fusion deck but, it's fun.

No Diabellstar engine. No Bonfire (yet, atleast but it would be nice for consistency but I digress). Just pure T.G.s. Why? Why not? Anyway, it's not meant to be a meta deck or anything, it's just a fun deck to play around and combo off.

So, how exactly do you wanna play this deck? This list is essentially T.G. Trident Launcher turbo, preferably with T.G. Hyper Librarian prior, and just go to town after that. So, cards.

Main Deck

• T.G. Striker & T.G. Warwolf  - I had to use these cards because there's still no Bonfire for added consistency, and I just actively refuse to play the expensive Diabellstar engine. Striker is literally just Cyber Dragon  and Warwolf's effect to summon itself isn't once per turn, so feel free to abuse that to your heart's content. Both of them equates to a Synchro Summon of a certain Limited Level 5 monster without your Normal Summon, and you already know where to go from there.

• T.G. Rocket Salamander  - Literally a custom card. Both your starter and extender in best ways possible.

• T.G. Gear Zombie  - Rocket Salamander's best friend. It's a Level 1 Tuner that can Special Summon itself for no cost nor unfulfillable condition, a recipe for a great extender.

• T.G. Screw Serpent  - Your usual target for Rocket Salamander. 2 is the best ratio, because either 1 or 3 makes it bricky.

• T.G. Drill Fish  - Your second target for T.G. Trident Launcher, usually. If you have some spare Main Deck space to fill, consider bumping it up to 2 or even 3, because it's just like Gear Zombie, except it can also be a monster removal, in which I actually did on my early iterations of this list.

• T.G. Tank Grub  - Your third target for T.G. Trident Launcher. I don't really like using it as a discard fodder since you'd ideally want to summon Hyper Librarian from the GY, but if you can't do that line, then it's not so bad. Careful with its effect to Summon a token so as to not clog your field though.

• x3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, Maxx "C", Droll & Lock Bird, & 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being - Quite a few number of hand traps. Ash is just ok, Maxx "C" is a pest that infest everyone's decks at this point and I'm tired of seeing it, Droll's a funny card against most decks like Floo and is also a counter to Maxx "C", and Nibiru here for the most part is just a Crossout Designator target.

• T.G. Limiter Removal  - Literally just Machina Redeployment. Play 3, it's a consistency piece.

• T.G. All Clear  - Another consistency piece. I only play 1 because it's searchable, but feel free to use 2-3 if you have free Main Deck slots, which I did in my previous versions of this list.

• Fire Formation - Tenki  - Searches Warwolf.

• Reinforcement of the Army  - Searches Striker.

• One for One  - Searches Rocket Salamander.

• Called by the Grave  & Crossout Designator  - Defensive cards.

• T.G. Close  - Negate that recurs itself. Yep.

• Infinite Impermanence  - Understandable. Also a Crossout target.

Extra Deck

• T.G. Glaive Blaster  - Your boss monster. It's removal, but it also allows easy ways to OTK your opponent.

• T.G. Halberd Cannon  - Your old boss monster. It's just a negate for Summons.

• Shooting Star Dragon T.G. EX  - This is NOT mandatory. It's just of a meme card. This could very well be a different Synchro 10 like Baronne de Fleur  or Satellite Warrior and it'll likely work better. I mean I guess it protects you against targeting monster effects. It also has great synergy with Glaive Blaster by banishing your Synchro Tuners for cost if you cope hard enough. I just included this in my list because it's funny.

• T.G. Blade Blaster  - An archetypal Level 10 Synchro. It's effects are pretty mid, but it can trigger Glaive Blaster, I suppose.

• PSY-Framelord Omega  - You can actually hand loop your opponent with this and Glaive Blaster, funnily enough.

• T.G. Hyper Librarian  - Broken in every Synchro spam deck, even more so in its own archetype.

• T.G. Power Gladiator  - An archetypal Level 5 non-Tuner Synchro that isn't Hyper Librarian.

• T.G. Wonder Magician  - An archetypal Level 5 Tuner Synchro monster that is also a back row removal.

• T.G. Over Dragonar  - Another custom card from Konami. Literally just YEP Soul Charge.

• T.G. Star Guardian  - An archetypal Level 5 Tuner Synchro monster extender.

• T.G. Mighty Striker  - A Level 2 Tuner Synchro monster (very relevant because it triggers Warwolf) that allows you to search any missing S/T you need, most likely either All Clear or Close.

• T.G. Recipro Dragonfly  - An archetypal Level 2 Synchro monster. Which is its better use. Ignore its effect, you'll most likely never use it. Even if you do, you're probably already doing way too much.

• T.G. Trident Launcher  - Make this as soon as possible. Crystron Halqifibrax  on steroids.

Final Thoughts

Rarely do I enjoy Synchro decks, but this one's actually fun. Even more so compared to Swordsoul that doesn't use actual Tuners, but that's another discussion. It can seem pretty expensive to build, but if you don't really care about the meta then hey, maybe give it a shot. It's a bit fragile against multiple disruptions though so do keep that in mind. Also, Bonfire would GREATLY improve this deck's consistency. As per usual, if you have any questions or thoughts, feel free to express them down in the comments and I'll respond to them as soon as I possibly can.

The main strategy of this deck is to use Zombie World to turn all monsters on the field and in the graveyards into Zombies, and then use Rivalry of Warlords to lock the opponent from summoning any non-Zombie monsters. This can severely hinder the opponent’s plays and prevent them from using their Extra Deck. Meanwhile, the deck can use cards like Uni-Zombie, Mezuki, and Book of Life to manipulate the levels and graveyard of the Zombies, and summon powerful Synchro and Link monsters like Doomking Balerdroch, Red-Eyes Zombie Necro Dragon, and Borreload Dragon. The deck can also use Super Polymerization to fuse the opponent’s monsters with The 13th Grave or any other Zombie to summon Dragonecro Nethersoul Dragon, a 3000 ATK beatstick that can halve the opponent’s monster’s ATK and inflict piercing damage.

The deck has some protection for The 13th Grave and other key cards, such as Shiranui Style Swallow’s Slash, which can destroy two cards on the field by banishing a Zombie from the hand or graveyard, and Needlebug Nest, which can mill five cards from the deck to the graveyard, potentially triggering the effects of Glow-Up Bloom, Necroworld Banshee, or Doomking Balerdroch. The deck can also use cards like Monster Reborn, One for One, and Foolish Burial to revive or send The 13th Grave or other Zombies from the deck or hand to the graveyard, where they can be more useful.

The deck is consistent and capable of winning games by disrupting the opponent’s strategy and overwhelming them with Zombie monsters. It can also adapt to different game scenarios by using the Extra Deck, which has options for removal, damage, and recovery.
lightsworns just to help

Kinda a fence-sitty deck that has the potentioal to burn with Sunny Snitch and Lil-la Rap, but also generally just play live-twin combo. I learned of a cool tech involving droplet that can play around imperm which is cool, also ghastly glitch can dump the Evil-twins boss monster if you have one of the links on the field, or onibi. Running some Xyz to play around cards like D-barrier. Pank can help deal with established boards without getting in the way of the Ki-sikil and Lil-La cyberse monster's effects. E-con works really well when you tribute one of the links cause you can summon the tributed monster back and if you tributed Lil-la, you can pop a card in adittion to grabbing an oponent's monster.

Looked into some swordsoul numbers and went with these ratios because the deck is generally consistent this way. Synchro zone is a cool tech pick and there is a combo you can do wtih gravity collapse as well, but it costs too much space in the deck and is unsearchable. I am running an extra deck that is pretty wrym heavy obviously, but there are some nice choices like adamancipator and barrone. PeP is also a neat choice, but strategist Longyuan burns so it isn't very nice, but it is a great option for busting out of near losses and its a guilty pleasure to play. Summit allows for a lot of extensions when drawn so it is increadibly good for recovering and pushing advantage though its not that nice to draw multiple of. Same reason we are running a Vessel, if you draw Taia you can dump a card for him to get a token plus some tenyi banishment extensions. Heavenly dragon circle allows for playing through interuption, same with droplet. Abyss dragon is good in this format if your opponent sets up a fire king island or the labrynth field spell. Though if your opponent isn't playing any of those then Iris allows you to play a bit during your opponents turn, plus I pulled a 25th of her so I am partial.

Extra deck is kinda weird, I mentioned the non-wryms that I am playing, I think they work very well in this deck, but I am only playing 1 Sinister because a lot of FZire decks play the charmer and thats killer if your opponent gets him. If they are playing fire, Chengying is a good because against sword soul you have a bit of graveyard interuption, kinda, but he is also a water that can't be stolen, plus 10 plus the level 1 adhara goes into PeP. The yangzing cards are good for extending your plays and helping you win over the board state going second, like in Baxia's case. I decided to run an abyss dweller because a lab deck may be running D-barrier, plus if you can't get to a synchro for whatever reason it can do a number interupting your opponents graveyard plays with fire king and snake-eyes.
There will be no turn 3

This is a deck I saw online that I wanted to mess around with. I think instead of the Weighbridge, E-con, and Safe-zones I can try putting the Terror root cards in. I really like how those cards play and I think they are interesting, plus the new Afteroot card might make them more consistent to set up ( Wannabee! helps too). Shadow-Imprisoning mirror is also really good at dealing with specific decks like Chaos, Unchained, and Lab, and it doesn't affect your deck except for number 96, who I would replace with Zeus, Accescode, or the charmer. Since you aren't garunteed those match-ups, I play them in the side. 

It's a different way of playing yugioh than what I normally run, but I like the Otter and the Melffys so I think this'll be a go to deck for me whenever I want to play a more casual game.

Ideal Flow => Use Neos Fusion to get Neos Kluger or activate "Fusion Destiny" to summon "Destiny HERO - Dominance" and draw a card, let it(Dominance) last to the next turn or wait till it's destroyed to summon Drilldark, Decider, and Defender back from the grave => Link 2 of the Destiny HERO's to summon Xtra HERO Infernal Deciever and use it's ability on Neos Kluger to draw Neos and Yubel to your hand(if not there already) => if a fusion card is not in your hand, then stall by linking Infernal Deciver to the remaining Destiny HERO to summon "Xtra Hero Dread Decimator" with a boosted ATK/DEF of 3000(3 Destiny HEROs + Destiny Fusion + Xtra HERO Infernal = +500 ATK) => Fuse Neos and Yubel to summon Neos Kluger. If Kluger is destroyed, Wiseman will be special summoned.

Contingencies: 1. Mask Change II can be used with all monster in deck except Stratos, Malicious Edge, and Wroughtweiler

2. Malicious Bane is great for blocking desruct effects and Malicious Fiend is great against cautios duelists who stall since it forces the opponen't battle phase.

3. Malicious Fiend with the current deck can only be summoned using Malicious Fiend and Yubel however, with Dark Calling, Yubel can be used even after being sent to the grave after being used to summon Kluger.

4. Malicious Edge can be drawn by using Infernal Deciever, Shadow Mist after being sent to the Grave(same for drawing Neos), Fusion Reserve or can be summoned using Vision Hero Vyon. Summon Vyon => Send Evil Hero Sinister Necrom to the Grave => Necrom's ability activates to Special summon Mallicious Edge

5. Elemental Hero Brave Neos + Favorite Hero + Neos Space has a minimum of 5000 ATK points

6. Neos Fusion/Miracle Contact on Rainbow Neos is used as a last defense if supporting monster(a monster that could be sacrificed for the ability) is not present.

Either normal summon Manju or one of the Impcantations to search out Chaos MAX Dragon or Chaos Form/Advanced Ritual Art, or use cards like The Melody of Awakening Dragon to search out Chaos MAX and Extra-Foolish Burial to send Herald of the Arc Light from your extra deck to the GY to activate its last effect. 

Once you have Chaos MAX on the field, use Creature Swap or Shien's Spy to give them a 0 DEF Impcantation monster then attack it with Chaos MAX to deal 8,000 damage and win the game.

Replacing the x3 copies of Alternatve and Jet Dragon with the other Impcantation cards and 1 copy of regular Chaos Dragon would technically make the deck a bit more consistent, but leaving them in gives easier access to alternate win conditions like Twin Burst Dragon and are themselves very good cards (plus that keeps the deck a majority dergons).

deck_name: WANTED: Seekers of Masters 1 - Guide to Snake-Eye (February 2024)
deck_excerpt: Step aside Albaz and Visas, it is time for Diabellstar and her lore cards to completely dominate as the face of competitive Yugioh!
deck_description:
The arrival of Diabellstar and her Snake-Eye/Sinful-Spoil cronies to Masterduel has completely changed the face of competitive ladder forever. As a stand alone pure deck (this time without its usual Fire Kings/Rescue-Ace compatriots), Snake-Eyes has is an extremely powerful deck! In fact, Snake-Eyes and it's variant decks is so powerful that it is nearly T1 or T0 since it is so dominant in the metagame!
 
Snake-Eyes Ash is accessible because 10 cards search it from deck, and including itself, it gives this deck THIRTEEN 1 card starters! The immense link spam potential, consistency and firepower of Snake-Eyes allows this deck to outpace, out-resource and overpower decks like Mannadium, Branded and Superheavy Samurai in a fashion to other Tier 1/0 decks did in the past like Tearlaments, Zoodiac and PePe. The support cards for the strategy like Snake-Eyes Poplar (insane custom card for Snake-Eyes) and Promethean Princess (incredibly accessible and generic Link-3 monster that direct buffs all fire strategies) grant Snake-Eyes near-immunity to devastating game-ending handtraps like Droll, Nibiru and even Dimension Shifter! 
 
Step aside Albaz and Visas, it is time for Diabellstar and her lore cards to completely dominate as the face of competitive Yugioh! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING

 
Diabellstar's crew is actually composed of 2 archetypes in her "pure" strategy: SNAKE-EYE (deck core) and the sub-archetype SINFUL-SPOILS (support for Snake-Eye). Since the deck is extremely consistent with a lot of 1 card starters, STAPLES form a large part of the deck. 
 
The SNAKE-EYE/SINFUL-SPOILS cards form the core of the deck. This deck core is maximized around searching or summoning from deck Snake-Eyes Ash, the heart and soul of the strategy. Snake-Eyes Ash starts up the entire gameplan, so 10 cards search it (3 Diabellstarr, 3 WANTED, 3 Original Sinful-Spoils, 1 One for One) in addition to having 3 copies of Ash granting a total of 13 starters! With that many starters, this deck is still very consistent, despite "Bonfire" not having been released yet in Masterduel. 1 Jet Synchron is a searchable level 1 fire monster to enable Synchro plays. 
 
The STAPLES featured in this deck are the usual suspects in Masterduel - the 12 card "Maxx C" package (3 Ash, 3 Maxx, 2 Called By, 1 Crossout and 2 Gamma + 1 Driver) so that you can come out on top of the "Maxx C Minigame." 1 Nibiru, Droll, Talents and Imperm are popular staples and Crossout targets to negate. There are a 15 total handtraps!
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Snake-Eye Fire King is a powerful combo deck that can link spam like no tomorrow. After the initial Snake-Eye combo, there are a ton of extenders such as Flamberge Dragon's "soul charge" of level 1 fires and Promethean Princess' summon of any fire monster from GY. Similarly to the "Cyberse pile" decks, Snake-Eye Fire King's immense swarming potential allow that enable the deck to link climb to incredible heights. Not only that, the deck is resilient enough to play through high impact handtraps like Nibiru, Droll, even Dimension Shifter! 
 
A singular uninterrupted Snake-Eyes Ash gets you through everything and provides you with a whopping many interruptions and incredible amounts of resources as follow-up for next turn. 
 
Snake-Eyes Ash =  1 targeted destruction of a monster (Promethean Princess) + 3 monster negates (Apollousa) + Linkuriboh (battle protection) + plenty of follow-up/full field/set-up GY for next turn. (If you have extenders, you also end on Savage Dragon's omni-negate and Baronne's omni-negate by summoning from deck Jet Synchron). 
  1. Normal summon Snake-Eyes Ash. Activate Snake Ash's effect to search for Snake Poplar from deck. 
  2. Activate Poplar's effect to summon itself from hand when searched. 
  3. Activate Poplar's effect when summoned to search for Original Sinful Spoils. 
  4. Link summon Linkuriboh using Poplar. Activate Poplar's effect when it leaves the field to place itself in the backrow. 
  5. Activate Original Sinful Spoils sending Poplar in the backrow to the GY to summon from deck Snake-Eyes Oak (If you have an extender, summon Jet Synchron instead for Synchro plays). 
  6. Activate Oak's on-summon effect to summon from the GY Ash. 
  7. Activate Oak's effect sending Linkuriboh to GY to summon from deck Flamberge Dragon. 
  8. Link summon I:P Masquerena using Flamberge Dragon + Ash. 
  9. Activate Flamberge Dragon's GY effect to summon from GY Ash + Poplar. 
  10. Link summon Promethean Princess using Poplar + I:P Masquerena. 
  11. Activate Promethean Princess' effect to summon from the GY Flamberge Dragon. 
  12. Activate Flamberge Dragon's effect to place in the backrow I:P Masquerena. 
  13. Link summon Amblowhale using Promethean Princess + Ash. 
  14. During your opponent's draw phase, summon from the backrow I:P Masquerena using Flamberge Dragon's effect. 
  15. During your opponent's main phase, link summon Apollousa using I:P Masquerena's effect using Amblowhale + Masqurena + Flamberge Dragon. 
  16. Activate Flamberge Dragon's GY effect to summon from GY Ash + Oak. 
  17. Activate in CL1 Ash to search for Poplar from deck, CL2 Oak to summon from GY Poplar. 
  18. Activate in CL1 Poplar to search from deck, CL2 Poplar to summon from hand. 
  19. At an opportune time, summon from the GY Linkuriboh by tributing Poplar. Reaching the GY, Poplar places a fire monster (usually itself) in the backrow. 
  20. When your opponent summons a monster, summon from the GY Promethean Princess by destroying your own fire monster and your opponent's summoned monster. 
GOING FIRST, a singular Snake-Eyes Ash grants you a triple monster negate with Apollousa, a targeted monster destruction with Promethean Princess, and lots of bodies + follow-up + set-up GY for next turn's OTK. If you have extenders beyond Ash (like Jet Synchron, One for One, or Snake-Eyes Divine Temple) you can also end on Heatsoul's draw 2, Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf's recovery from the GY of a fire monster (like Ash Blossom)! Next turn, you can OTK easily with tons of link material to finish the game with the likes of Accesscode Talker. Remember this is from 1 card, so your hand may also contain one to several of the 15 handtraps!
 
GOING SECOND, the Snake-Eyes strategy features a ton of handtraps to weaken your opponent's gamestate or potentially end their turn on a suboptimal board so you can start comboing yourself. As you combo up, you can methodically remove your opponent's field using Flamberge Dragon's non-destruction removal, Knightmare Phoenix's S/T destruction, Knightmare Unicorn's shuffle, and Accesscode can be made for up to 3 pops due to the different attribute link material in the GY (dark-Linkuriboh, fire-Knightmake Phoenix, light-Selene), 
 

GENERAL TIPS

  • Snake-Eyes does a lot of actions that involves having no monsters on the field - meaning that Psy-Frame Gamma is almost always live! Alot of players on ladder leave their Ash Blossom for the Original Sinful Spoils summoning a card from deck, and since the card leaves your field empty, you can Gamma their Ash Blossom! When that interaction happens, people usually leave. 
  • If you manage to summon Gamma + Driver on your turn, you can summon Borreload Savage Dragon for an additional negate. Just be sure your GY is set up with a link monster! A cool interaction is that you can also send to the GY the equipped link monster to the GY as the cost of your Snake-Eye cards!
  • If you lose out on the Maxx "C" minigame, try to end your board on Flamberge Dragon. For the price of allowing your opponent to draw 1 more card, you can end on a 3000 ATK body and follow-up for next turn since the card floats into your searchers in the GY. 
  • Hiita and Dharc can summon a monster from your opponent's GY (for example, summon your opponent's Ash Blossom or D.D. Crow) and you can either make Selene (typically for Accesscode) or more importantly, Promethean Princess. if your GY is already set-up, this play allows you to get back to your gameplan by summoning a crucial Fire monster from the GY, like Snake-Eyes Ash, Poplar or Flamberge Dragon. 
  • If you have Snake-Eyes Ash and you drew into Original Sinful Spoils already, when you search with Poplar take Snake-Eyes Divine Temple instead so that it's an additional extender. The extra card in the backrow serves as an extender for your Snake-Eyes cost to send a card on the field to the GY.  
  • Snake-Eyes summons so many times (even on the opponent's turn!) that you'd sometimes find yourself in the awkward position of having no more space on your board! Be careful of this scenario. A good way to get around this situation during your opponent's turn is to link away as much monsters as possible for I:P Masquerena. 
  • Since all your interruption is centered around your monsters, be careful about your Apollousa being stolen by your opponent (happens surprisingly a lot). A "talents" or change of heart on your Apollousa is often devastating and is enough to break your board since you'll be facing down your own mass negates. 
  • You'll encounter a lot of Snake-Eye mirror matches on ladder. When facing a rival Snake-Eyes player, negate your opponent's Flamberge Dragon, especially by using Crossout or Called By the Grave. This prevents their target removal of your cards and severely limits their link spam. Also, try to prevent your opponent from summoning or using Hiita, since she can also use your entire GY with all it's effect monsters!
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
     

CONCLUDING COMMENTARY

 

BUCKLE IN DUELISTS, the Fire Format is upon us! The forecast to our metagame is cloudy, with a extremely high chance of firestorms! 

Riding on the back of this maelstrom is our favourite delinquent treasure hunter adventurer! Diabellstar is the face of this upcoming Tier 1/0 metagame, since her Snake-Eyes enable all fire decks with level 1 fire monsters to reach new heights of competitive power. Before the other crucial cards like Fire King and Infernoid come out, Pure Snake-Eyes is already extremely potent at what it does. The strategy provides near infinite link material, Flamberge's "soul charge" for level 1 fire monsters, immense recursion and Promethean Princess's monster reborn! 
 
It is safe to say that Masterduel ladder will be dominated by this femme fatale and her gang for the next couple months, until she gets the inevitable banhammer for being too powerful. Until then, lets burn away all opposition with Pure Snake-Eyes!
 
GLHF Duelists!

The Gates of Dark World is a soft once per turn, so don't hesitate to banish Genta, Gateman of Dark World an additional time to keep your combo going. 

Called by the Grave should probably be main deck but I'm a greedy bitch. 

Springans Merrymaker is literally a free Saryuja Skull Dread or Underworld Goddess of the Closed World if they have a monster for The White Woman to use as Material.

When going second, make fusion summoning Grapha, Dragon Overlord of Dark World your top priority because he can turn an opponent's interaction into a massive advantage for you.

This deck fills up the board a lot, which is the primary function of both I:P Masquerena and Knightmare Unicorn . Recall that, because it discards as a cost rather than an effect, Knightmare Unicorn does not trigger our DW cards.

This deck would have Chaos Angel if I was not poor. It's so good and absurdly easy for this deck to bring out especially when going second. 

Masquerade the Blazing Dragon is only in our extra so we can pitch any Fiend (which is all DW cards) using Branded in High Spirits , and although the deck can summon it with Polymerization , there's no reason to because it basically eats your whole turn to do it.

Sprind the Irondash Dragon is in there for the same reason, to pitch a Regulus in case you sideboard him in and draw both Reguli.

Don't be overzealous in using the graveyard effects of Reign-Beaux, Overking of Dark World and Grapha, Dragon Lord of Dark World , it is very easy to end up with a hand full of shit and no way to get rid of it.

The Zombie Vampire may seem like an odd inclusion, but it's literally a free card, and also if you take one of their monsters with either Snoww, Unlight of Dark World or Grapha, Dragon Lord of Dark World you can just keep their monster hostage underneath it. 

Pot of Avarice should always return as many Danger! monsters as possible, in particular Danger!? Jackalope? , Danger! Bigfoot! ,and Danger! Ogopogo! 

If you have the misfortune of drawing Ken the Warrior Dragon ,Use either Springans Kitt or Saryuja Skull Dread to Spin him.

Ceruli, Guru of Dark World is only good to add when you have other mechanisms of discarding (i.e. Danger! monsters, Branded in High Spirits ) 

Danger! Ogopogo! should always bin Danger! Chupacabra! since its a Fiend that you can banish with The Gates of Dark World 

Number 1: Infection Buzzking is mostly just there because there aren't that many good Rank 8's for this deck to make, and it's very funny to watch your opponent's eyes widen as they read it.

A previous version of this deck ran Therion "Reaper" Fum because Danger! Nessie! is an Aqua monster. Trust me, you're better off without it.
Test Deck for Invasion of Chaos
Pure T.G deck with some staples for Casual Play

Branded fusion gives another way of getting Lo or Saffira into the grave which can act as an extender through handtraps

Example branded fusion extender through droll: open Saffira + Branded fusion and 3 handtraps, activate saffira add skull+send spell, get drolled, activate branded fusion use albaz + Lo for albion, albion into lubellion using albaz and albion, lubellion discard a handtrap to make mirrorjade using banished albion and albaz, use saffira to ritual skull guardian over lubellion, activate Lo in grave to special, activate Lo to set either spell or trap, trap can be used to summon Old man sauravis by shuffling ritual spell or spell can be used for follow up. Lo is summoned on the 5th summon so this line is nib proof.

End board is the same as pure with an added Mirrorjade for disruption and sends albion for a follow up branded fusion

Figure it out

"Ey boss Traptrix isn't meta!"
"Just throw Reincarnation as a hand rip"
"But boss, how we search it?"
"like this"

Welcome to the world's worst theory deck. This is a Traptrix deck with slight Trickstar engine just to play Reincarnation. Time-Tear is the double normal of choice, but it can be replaced with Double Summon if you want hand traps in main.

My baka otouto didn't wanna build a decklist before ordering the new stuff (he's still behind on Simorgh), so I built it for him so he doesn't waste any money. Lucky you! You get to reap the benefits! Idk how many copies of Imperm he has, but it really is the best handtrap, especially for these birbs. If you have to, sub copies with Effect Veiler. He was using Evenly Matched, but the battle phase is basically this deck's win condition. You don't wanna give your opponent the chance to field bigger numbers.

I was originally going to pass up on Glorious Bright, but after pulling one, I realized a searchable negate is EXACTLY what RRs needed, and it's now searchable with Brave Strix. I doubled up on every extender in the extra deck but Arsenal Falcon, who only needs to resolve once anyway.

I'm not gonna tell you every line of play in this deck 'cause I don't wanna help my brother beat me any more often than he doesn't. Get out there and have fun ridin' those Baberaptors! Yeehaww!

This is the deck I'm taking to regionals in a couple of weeks.

The idea is to use the new dino support to end with a board of Secret village of the spellcasters, charmer (to make the filed spell live) lars, UCT, and gigantozowler.

The combo is fairly consistent, and there aren't that many hands that can't net you the end board, but I haven't really tested it against the current meta.

My thougts on the non engine are as follows:
.- droll and lock is main deck no question
 - fenrir is too good not to play it
 - could force my way into liberating three more slots, to run either super poly, or unicorn/birth, at the cost of risking an opening hand with the combo pieces, and puting a break on your own combo.

deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Derek Nguyen

Tournament: The Side Deck Remote Duel WCQ Regional – February 18th 2024

Placement: 1st Place

Crash your Chaos MAX into a 0 DEF monster to one-tap everyone at locals. The wins will feel great, trust me. This deck goes blind second. If you go first, you will need to find a way to stall.

Chose the Drytron package over Impcantation, for consistency and flexibility in case you get interrupted. Drytron can recover, Imps just can't.

Basic combo line :

  1. Activate Drytron Alpha Thuban, Tribute Drytron Zeta Aldhibah to Summon Itself, search Cyber Angel Benten 
  2. Activate Drytron Zeta Aldhibah in the GY, Tribute Cyber Angel Benten to Summon itself, search Meteonis Drytron 
  3. Activate Cyber Angel Benten in the GY, search Diviner of the Herald 
  4. Xyz your two Drytrons into Drytron Mu Beta Fafnir, activate its effect, send Drytron Gamma Eltanin 
  5. Normal Summon Diviner of the Herald, send Herald of the Arc Light and turn Diviner into a Level 6
  6. Activate Herald of the Arc Light  to search Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon 
  7. Activate your Meteonis Drytron, detach both materials from Drytron Mu Beta Fafnir to Ritual Summon Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon
  8. Activate Creature Swap or Shien's Spy to give Drytron Mu Beta Fafnir to your opponent
  9. Battle Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon on Drytron Mu Beta Fafnir for 8000 damage and game.

Ideally, you want to open Creature Swap or Shien's Spy, that enables the OTK.  If you open a Cyber Angel Benten, your Drytron Alpha Thuban can go fetch the Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon directly, and bypass the need to Normal Summon Diviner of the Herald. That frees you to Normal Summon Knightmare Corruptor Iblee, and link it away to have a 0 DEF body on the opponent's field another way.

Options and tips :

- I chose to not run Pot of Riches, too risky to ban the 1 copy of Meteonis Drytron or Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon.
- With Alpha, Zeta, Gamma, a copy of Benten, and either Herald or N'tss in GY at the end of step 6, Pot of Avarice also works.
- Triple Tactics Talent is used for draw power exclusively, no need to take control of an opponent's monster, your win condition is to give one away to obliterate it. Counterpoint is if the enemy has a big bad towers, or a high ATK body, to use with Meteonis Drytron.
- If you have that kind of bling, Triple Tactics Thrust is a fantastic addition to the deck, to fetch Creature Swap or Shien's Spy directly from the deck.
- Foolish Burial is used to send Drytrons to GY for revival. Prioritize Alpha and Zeta, if you have not opened them, then Delta for draw power.
- Great budget option for Diviner is Manju of the Ten Thousand Hands. If so, you can remove the N'tss and Herald copies in your Extra Deck, and play some more Knightmares or Downerd / Zeus package with Kiki (see below). Hopefully, Diviner gets reprinted soon (RA02, my beloved, please).

Extra Deck :

- Elder Entity N'tss and Herald of the Arc Light are self-explanatory. Diviner of the Herald sends one to the GY, to either destroy or search. Herald, in particular, can even be summoned if your Diviner gets Impermed, then you just link it away to trigger the effect anyway.
- Kikinagashi Fucho, in this list, is basically a Rank 1 Bagooska. Use it to wait a turn if you are missing a combo piece. With modifications to the list, you can even include Downerd Magician and Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder to have a single boardwipe. Careful not to ban it with Pot of Extravagance though.
- The Knightmare package is great here. Either destroy or send back, while putting Drytrons and possibly Herald in GY, for them to trigger effects. They are also not important enough to be an immediate loss if Pot of Extravagance banishes them. Great helping hands.
- Linguriboh to link away Iblee, 3 of them to be absolutely sure to keep at least one after a Pot of Extravagance.
- Linkuriboh to link away the Drytron you summoned with Drytron Nova, so you can trigger effect from GY.
- Relinquished Anima if your opponent has a poorly placed scary monster. Bonus effect : stealing monsters feels good.

deck_excerpt: Blind Second Sky Striker for the 2024 Synchro/Link Festival! Blow stuff up and win quick easy games with Raye!
deck_description:
Blind Second Sky Striker for the 2024 Synchro/Link Festival! Blow stuff up and win quick easy games with Raye!

The idea behind Blind Second Sky Strikers is to wipe out most if not all of your opponent's resources that they slap down on the board going first, and then close out the match with Sky Striker's grind game. Everyone in the Link/Synchro event is slapping down their entire extra deck and main deck and hand into the board going first and you'll just wipe all that away with your ~20ish boardbreakers!

If you want quick easy games to grind for the Synchro/Link Festival, Blind Second Sky Striker is perfect for that!

If you have any questions about this deck, feel free to ask me in the comments below!

GLHF Duelists!

Pure Junk Synchron deck for casual play

A Runick build sporting an Ice Barrier engine with the upcoming support.

The Runick engine has an interesting position in the metagames to come, doing good against Labrynth and doing ok against the fire decks, while the Ice Barrier engine opens strong options against Runick variants and has various ways to pressure the previously mentionned. Overall you don't have really bad match ups, Branded being threatened by the toolbox induced by the Ice Barrier engine.

This variant selling points are it's draw power (draw 7 first turn) with more stability and resilience than the Fur Hire one. Indeed it can easily play around Droll and Nibiru, and generally whistand multiple hand traps. The multiple searchers and extenders means you have a fair number of lines, making opponnent's hand traps more difficult to time and value, you can also directly synchro climb without Runick bodies. Finally the ability Ice Barrier has to make a Crocodragon for 4 in one card is a huge asset to grind in go second games since you can use your entire hand to climb boards then just draw a new one.

Like other Runick variant you definitely don't like Shifter and Droplet, even if your draw power will be a good way to finish your turn with wide combination of Runicks and survive the last mentioned. Part of your basic boards takes Super Poly, but you can play around if the card is a thing. The Voiceless Voice match up by itself isn't bad but can be a lot more difficult if your opponent has double Barrier, as it will cut the interactive side of your Runick spells and prevent your SP to ban 1 on the board.
