deck_excerpt: The time has come to harness the power of advanced machinery and strategic prowess with the all-new Yu-Gi-Oh! Starter Deck - Qliphort!
deck_description:
Welcome, duelists, to the cutting-edge realm of dueling innovation! The time has come to harness the power of advanced machinery and strategic prowess with the all-new Yu-Gi-Oh! Starter Deck - Qliphort! This formidable deck introduces a fusion of futuristic technology and ancient mysticism, offering duelists a gateway to a dimension where mighty Qliphort monsters reign supreme.

As you embark on this dueling journey, prepare to witness the convergence of mechanical marvels and mystical energies, culminating in a deck that not only stands the test of time but reshapes the very fabric of the dueling battlefield. Qliphort monsters, with their sleek designs and unparalleled abilities, promise an unforgettable dueling experience that transcends the boundaries of conventional strategies.

Harness the power of Pendulum Summoning and watch as the Qliphort pendulum scales open portals to summon forth powerful monsters that defy the laws of dueling physics. Unleash the might of colossal constructs like Qliphort Genius and Qliphort Monolith, each boasting unique abilities that can turn the tide of any duel in your favor.

Prepare yourself for a duel like never before, as Starter Deck - Qliphort invites you to master the fusion of technology and ancient energies, paving the way for a new era of dueling domination. Are you ready to command the Qliphort forces and ascend to victory? The future of dueling awaits, and it's time to forge your path with Starter Deck - Qliphort!

deck_excerpt: Duelists, prepare to embark on a thrilling journey into the heart of the insect kingdom with the latest marvel in dueling evolution......
deck_description:
Duelists, prepare to embark on a thrilling journey into the heart of the insect kingdom with the latest marvel in dueling evolution - the Yu-Gi-Oh! Starter Deck - Beetrooper! This deck invites you to immerse yourself in the world of highly organized insect armies, where strategic precision and swarming tactics converge to create a force that is as relentless as it is formidable.

As you delve into the Starter Deck - Beetrooper, you'll find yourself surrounded by a buzzing legion of insect warriors led by powerful commanders like Beetrooper Scout and Beetrooper Scale Bomber. These mighty creatures, with their intricate designs and synergistic abilities, lay the groundwork for an insectoid revolution that promises to leave an indelible mark on the dueling landscape.

The Beetrooper deck introduces exciting new gameplay dynamics, where teamwork and collaboration among your insect allies are paramount. Utilize the deck's unique swarming capabilities to overwhelm your opponents and dominate the field, as you summon forth Beetrooper Hive and Beetrooper Squadron to establish your insect supremacy.

Get ready to experience the fusion of nature's resilience and strategic brilliance, as Starter Deck - Beetrooper takes you on a journey where the smallest creatures wield the mightiest powers. The insect realm awaits your command – are you prepared to lead the Beetrooper swarm to victory and etch your name into the annals of dueling history? It's time to spread your wings and conquer the duel with Starter Deck - Beetrooper!

deck_excerpt: Duelists, prepare to embrace the shadows and delve into the eerie realms of the afterlife with the Yu-Gi-Oh! Starter Deck - Skull Servant!
deck_description:
Duelists, prepare to embrace the shadows and delve into the eerie realms of the afterlife with the Yu-Gi-Oh! Starter Deck - Skull Servant! Unearth the mysteries of the netherworld as you command a legion of skeletal warriors led by the infamous Skull Servant himself. This haunting deck promises a dueling experience like no other, where the line between the living and the undead becomes blurred.

 

Starter Deck - Skull Servant beckons you to embrace the darkness, as you summon forth an army of skeletal soldiers such as Wightprincess, Wightmare, and, of course, the iconic Skull Servant. These undead entities rise from the graveyard with a thirst for victory, ready to shroud the duel in an aura of spine-chilling terror.

 

Discover the synergy between these skeletal apparitions, as they weave a tapestry of doom across the dueling field. Unleash the potential of powerful spells and traps like "The Lady in Wight" and "King of the Skull Servants," and witness the might of your ghostly horde grow with every fallen soul.

 

The Starter Deck - Skull Servant invites you to dance with the macabre, wielding the power of the undead to conquer your adversaries. Are you prepared to peer into the abyss and command an army of spectral warriors to victory? The shadows whisper your name, beckoning you to join the spectral ranks. It's time to embrace the darkness and reign supreme with the Starter Deck - Skull Servant!

deck_excerpt: Duelists, prepare to confront the ancient forces that lay dormant beneath the earth's surface with the Yu-Gi-Oh! Starter Deck - Earthbound!
deck_description:
Duelists, prepare to confront the ancient forces that lay dormant beneath the earth's surface with the Yu-Gi-Oh! Starter Deck - Earthbound! Embark on a journey to unearth the primal power of the Earthbound Immortals, as this formidable deck transcends the boundaries between the living and the eternal forces that lie within the core of the earth.

 

The Starter Deck - Earthbound beckons you to channel the raw energies of the Earthbound Immortals, colossal beings with otherworldly abilities that can reshape the very foundations of dueling. Unleash the might of Earthbound Immortal Ccapac Apu, Earthbound Immortal Uru, and their kin as they rise from the depths to claim dominance over the duel.

 

As you traverse the mysterious landscapes of the Earthbound realm, your deck will be fortified with supporting creatures and spells, each intricately designed to harmonize with the colossal might of the Earthbound Immortals. Unearth the secrets of the Ancients with field spells like "Earthbound Whirlwind" and traps such as "Earthbound Revival," as you orchestrate a symphony of destruction that echoes through the ages.

 

The Starter Deck - Earthbound invites you to embrace the power that slumbers beneath the earth's surface and command the mightiest beings ever to walk the dueling realm. Are you prepared to awaken the ancient forces and forge a path to victory? The earth trembles in anticipation, and the time has come to command the primordial powers with the Starter Deck - Earthbound!

deck_excerpt: Duelists, brace yourselves for a mystical convergence of ancient runes and arcane energies with the Yu-Gi-Oh! Starter Deck - Runick!
deck_description:
Duelists, brace yourselves for a mystical convergence of ancient runes and arcane energies with the Yu-Gi-Oh! Starter Deck - Runick! Embark on a journey steeped in mysticism and magic as you unravel the secrets of the Runick realm, a deck that weaves the threads of ancient symbols into a tapestry of powerful spellcasting and strategic prowess.

In the Starter Deck - Runick, you will delve into a world where the power of runes takes center stage. Command enigmatic creatures and sorceries, each inscribed with ancient symbols that resonate with the very essence of magic. From the mighty Runick Archmage to the elusive Runebound Guardian, every card in this deck unveils a new layer of mystical might.

Immerse yourself in the art of spellcasting as you harness the energy of powerful runic spells and enchantments, setting the stage for a duel where the very fabric of reality is at your command. Unleash the potential of spell cards like "Runic Invocation" and "Arcane Nexus," and watch as the ancient runes manifest in spectacular displays of magical prowess.

The Starter Deck - Runick invites you to master the arcane arts, combining the wisdom of the ancients with your dueling skills to forge a path to victory. Are you ready to decipher the runes, unlock their secrets, and ascend to a level of mastery previously unseen? The mystical winds beckon, and the time has come to wield the power of the runes with the Starter Deck - Runick!

Witness the synergy of these mighty creatures as they unleash their geological might, combining to create an unstoppable force that transcends the sands of time.

 

The Starter Deck - Adamancipator invites you to embrace the spirit of discovery, commanding the rock-solid forces of the past to shape the future of your dueling destiny. Are you ready to excavate the power of ancient civilizations, uncover the mysteries buried in the earth, and triumph as the master of the Adamancipator deck? The stones are set, and the time has come to carve your path to victory with the Starter Deck - Adamancipator!

deck_name: Delicious Veggie Curry! A Kabayama / Sartyr Deck
deck_excerpt: Delicious Veggie Curry! A reinterpretation of a possible curry deck for Kabayama/Sartyr from Yu-Gi-Oh! GX, fighting as Curry Mask.
deck_description:
Delicious Veggie Curry! A  reinterpretation of a possible curry deck for Kabayama/Sartyr from Yu-Gi-Oh! GX, fighting as Curry Mask. Since basically all of his monsters, including his boss Curry Fiend Don Roux, and his Spice cards, don't exist, I've reformatted the deck into a Plant beatdown hybrid deck, using all the most tasty vegetables Curry Mask could find.

In place of his Spices, Curry Mask now uses Aroma monsters, specifically Marjoram (Bay Leaf), Bergamot and Rosemary, three aromatic herbs you might find used in curry recipies. His new boss monster is Aromalilith Magnolia, because a fragrant, aromatic vegetarian dish feels like an appropriate replacement for Curry Fiend Don Roux.

Everything else is pretty self-explanatory, though I would have liked to include Spy-C-Spy because obviously it's curry based, but it interferes with Solidarity.

A different take on the Tenpai game plan, instead of breaking boards, prevent it. Your opening hand should has a 75% of having at least 2 starters on turn 2 (93% for 1 starter) and the rest being handtraps should be enough to minmise the opponent's board.

The reasoning behind this version is that your handtraps also help to insulate your comboes by popping unexpected floodgates and some form of GY hate. It makes for a more fun and interactive game, but may end up being the more powerful version of Tenpai yet.

deck_excerpt: Imagine Runick's +3 draw with Snake-Eye's +8 one card combo...
deck_description:
Runick Snake-Eyes combines the splashable toolbox spell advantage strategy of Runick with the most powerful deck of the "Fire Format," Snake-Eyes! Just try to imagine your usual Snake-Eyes deck but with more draw power, consistency, but with less handtraps and with more Runick cards (they kind of function like handtraps/boardbreakers anyways). Shoutout to the OG Runick mastermind Joshua Schmidt to inventing and teaching me, one of his stream viewers this strategy - ultimately inspiring me to make this article/video. 
 
After your usual Runick shenanigans (Draw 3 with Runick Fountain), you go for full Snake-Eyes combo complete with I:P Masquerena, Flamberge Dragon, Promethean Princess and Amblowhale. This strategy generally has extra bodies due to the Runick spells all functioning "Instant Fusion," so most hands can end on a board with Heatsoul as well! Runick cards double as boardbreakers we well, allowing them to be used as your opening salvo to simplify your opponent's gamestate, so you can full combo with Snake-Eyes. In addition to searches, this deck can draw an obscene total of up to 6 cards during your turn and your opponent's turn (3 with Runick Fountain, 2 with Heatsoul and 1 with WANTED:Seeker). 
 
Even if your opponent stops one side of your strategy (say they ash Hugin so you can't search Fountain), you can always pivot to the other archetype (Snake-Eyes) and full combo since all their handtraps/interactions are already used up! Remember, Fountain allows you to draw up to 3 cards and a singular uninterrupted Snake-Eyes Ash is a net +8 so your opponent will get out-resourced either way! 
 
Soon enough, you'll be out-grinding  your opponent while controlling their strategy to death! Runick Snake-Eyes also inherently a lot of attack power on board due to the immense link summoning powerhouse that is Snake-Eyes combined with Runick's extenders, so you can even push for game after your battle phase skip! 
 
An interesting interaction of Runick and Snake-Eyes is that The Original Sinful-Spoils, Snake-Eye Ash, Snake-Eye Oak and Worldsea Dragon Zealantis can clear your Extra Monster Zone of its Runick Fusion monster, so you can keep summoning more Runick monsters through your spells. This would allow more chances to activate Runick Spells for a possible extra couple draws with Runick Fountain while simultaneously providing extenders to link summoning. Both decks inherently synergize with each other, allowing for more resources to be generated from both Runick and Snake-Eye strategies. 
 
Runick adds extra power to Snake-Eye's monster-based interactions since it adds novel variety to the interruptions available to the deck - Runick's quick play spells! In addition to Promethean Princess' pop, Apollousa's 2-4 monster negates and Linkuriboh's monster protection, your opponent will have to deal with the plethora of toolbox quick-play spells in your hand. This means that even cards like Evenly Matched, Dark Ruler No More or a Nibiru boardwipe can cannot completely finish you since you can lean back to either your Runick or Snake-Eye cards. 
 
Runick is simple to use enough and its been around for a couple years now, so there is no explanation needed there. For a more detailed guide on Snake-Eyes, click here for my earlier article on the strategy. 

GLHF Duelists!

Get Gouki The Master Ogre on the field, use Gouki Finishing Move, and battle away. Easy stuff. 

This list in heavily inspired by JaspmanZX, see his list here : https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/gouki-410727.

Best possible combo :

  1. Normal Summon Gouki Suprex, activate effect to Special Summon other Gouki (ex. Gouki Twistcobra).

  2. Link Summon Gouki Jet Ogre, activate Goukis' effects in GY to add Gouki Headbatt and another Gouki (ex. Gouki Riscorpio).

  3. Activate Headbatt effect to Special Summon it discarting Riscorpio.

  4. Link Summon Gouki Thunder Ogre, activate Headbatt effect to add another Gouki (ex. Gouki Iron Claw).

  5. Extra Normal Summon Iron Claw.

  6. Link Summon Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess, activate Iron Claw effect to add Gouki Re-Match.

  7. Activate Re-Match special summoning Riscorpio and another Gouki.

  8. Link Summon Codebreaker Virus Swordsman, activate effect to Special Summon Codebreaker Zero Day and activate Riscorpio effect to add Re-Match.

  9. Link Summon Codebreaker Virus Berserker, activate effect to Special Summon back the Virus Swordsman and Zero Day.

  10. Link Summon them into The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche to the right zone.

  11. Activate Bardiche effect sending The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots to GY and setting The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigandine.

  12. Activate Brigandine summoning itself as a monster.

  13. Link Summon Gouki The Powerload Ogre with Berserker and Brigandine.

  14. Activate Silent Boots effect in GY banishing itself to add Phantom Knights' Fog Blade, set it and End Turn.

Some changes :

- Effect Veiler to bait out interrupts or Battle Phase effects that might prevent the OTK.
- One for One, to get Gouki Guts or Gouki Octostretch from Deck, link it away with Linkuriboh, and activate effect to get Gouki Suprex, as the best Normal Summon.
- Reasoning, since almost every Gouki is of a different Level, so it will most likely resolve every time.
- Small World, and use Effect Veiler as a bridge. Only Gouki Guts and Gouki Octostretch cannot be search, since both Level 1 and 0 DEF.
- Triple Tactics Talent is always nice. This deck is very sensible to interrupts, every single Gouki effect can be Ashed. It helps either recover, or removing an opponent's monster for easier OTK.
- Couple of floodgates (booooo), since you play mostly EARTH Warriors.
- Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax in place of Gouki The Blade Ogre, since quite frankly, it might be the worst Gouki Link monster (one man's opinion). Also, Avramax can help get rid of big bads that can only be outed in battle.
- Knightmare Phoenix in place of Accesscode Talker, because budget. Simple as. RA02 cannot come soon enough.

deck_excerpt: An enjoyable dark magician deck with runicks toxic playstyle
deck_description: Main target of the deck is to stall out the game and destroy the resources
Deciding on main skullmeister and cyclone, veiler instead of nibiru, ghost belle instead of meister, more copies of soul release, maybe a kaiju/sphere mode,
Just try it ^ ^ I think, it's the one best consistency Yubel - Unchained deck at the moment

Mostly got the idea from some random Karpath video I watched a while back. 

Basically the concept is to abuse Eccentric Boy by making level 8 Synchro bodies with high stats (Archfiend, Fighter, etc etc) to mitigate the drawback effects, then when they are removed from play as per Eccentric's effect you can cheese them out with Escape with their effects intact. You wanna be drawing level 5's in that case for the hand, best choices are 3x Thunder Dragon (consistency/cost both met) alongside a pair of Cyber Dragons and 3x Sirocco for the Vayu stuff; that helps with board pressure and to make the Escapes less dead in hand.

The targets for Eccentric are generally cards that are going to be a mix of being good with/without their effects. Archfiend is 3k already so that's a plus regardless. There's a good mix of cards available that I'd dare say it becomes more of a toolbox if you can get at least one of them out and banished, especially ones like Thought Ruler or Dark End which are both also valid targets for the strat. It's certainly not amazing yet for the gimmick it works, not many decks can throw out pressure like that with one or two cards required. 

The build otherwise is pretty inoffensive. Chaos Sorc admittedly is a bit jank in here however with all of the targets available it was never a brick when it got drawn so I can't say much else about it. Legacy copies are there to actually see the plays more with the additional upside of maybe baiting out removal in the right conditions. Side Board was mostly just generic. Virus with Eccentric targets is possible; requires a bit too much resource-wise to be viable sadly. Maybe another time.
WIP, feels good to play, deciding on impemanence due to the superheavys, but i like it more than veiler

pp
Red-Eyes takes on the meta.

This deck focuses on utilizing Tri-Horned Dragon as its core engine, enabling powerful effects and summoning of high-level monsters.

Deck Strategy:

  • The core strategy revolves around Tri-Horned Dragon. Use Trade-In to discard it and draw 2 cards, then use Decoy Dragon to Special Summon it from your Deck. This enables powerful effects like Deck Devastation Virus and Eradicator Epidemic Virus, banishing your opponent's monsters while potentially setting up your own graveyard for Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon.
  • Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon is your primary win condition. Use discarded cards from Trade-In, Allure of Darkness, and Common Charity to fulfill its summoning cost and dominate the field with its high attack power.
  • Dark Magician provides additional DARK attribute synergy, allowing you to activate Allure of Darkness and potentially be discarded for Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon.
  • Monster Reborn helps recover key monsters like Tri-Horned Dragon or Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon for further plays.
  • Pot of Desires and Upstart Goblin accelerate your draw engine, while Common Charity allows for card filtering and discarding for Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon.
  • Solemn Strike and Torrential Tribute provide defensive options against your opponent's threats.

A New Way to play Dragon Link with Snake-Eye engine.

Snake-Eye engine combo can makes you have Saryuja Skull Dread chain link 2 with Flamberge to draw 4 take 1 and re summon 2 Snake-Eye mons.

Engine combo: WANTED or Diabellstar the Black Witch (DBW) (Make sure you have 1 monster to NS in hand)

1./ Play WANTED to add DBW to hand ==> send 1 card from hand to SS DBW ==> use DBW to set Original

2./ Play Original to SS Ash ==> use Ash effect add and SS Poplar ==> use Poplar effect add Devine Temple (field spell).

3./ Use Poplar SS Linkuriboh ==> use Poplar effect set it to S/T zone ==> use Ash effect send itself and Poplar to SS Oak ==> Oak effect SS any Snake-Eye mons in GY

4./ Play Devine Temple to set remain Snake-Eye mons in GY to S/T zone ==> use Oak effect to send itself and 1 mons in S/T zone to SS Flamberge

5./ At this time your field will have 3 monsters (Flamberge + Linkuriboh + 1 Snake-Eye mons) ==> NS 1 mons in hand to SS Saryuja Skull Dread

6./ Saryuja and Flamberge will make a chainlink (Use Saryuja 1 and Flamberge 2) ==> Saryuja effect draw 4 cards and return 3 cards + Flamberge effect SS 2 Snake-Eye monsters in GY.

7./ Then you have 3 monster on the field (Saryuja + 2 Snake-Eye monsters) and don't forget, you still have Saryuja's effect to SS 1 mons in hand.

==> Depend on which cards did you have when finishing step No.6, you can play Dragon Link combos or use 4 monsters on the field to SS Apollousa.

Hope you like the Engine and this Powerful deck.

The basic strategy of this deck is to use cards like Dragon Shrine, Trade-In, and Foolish Burial to send Tri-Horned Dragon and other high-level dragons to the graveyard, and then revive them with cards like Return of the Dragon Lords, Silver’s Cry, and Call of the Haunted. You can also use The White Stone of Ancients and The White Stone of Legend to search for Blue-Eyes White Dragon and its variants, which can help you summon powerful synchro and xyz monsters. Dragon Core Hexer is a level 8 tuner that can be used to synchro summon Giganticastle, a level 9 monster with 3100 ATK that can beat Tri-Horned Dragon in a battle. Skill Drain is a trap card that can negate the effects of all face-up monsters on the field, which can give Tri-Horned Dragon an advantage over most monsters.

deck_excerpt: But...where was Yugi when the Westfold fell?
deck_description:
The idea behind this deck is pretty simple: Pendulum summon multiple Barrier Statues at the same time to lock your opponent out of special summons on your way to drawing Exodia. You might need to double up on Statues with Winds banned (I recommend Inferno rn). So open with your Performapals, set those scales (without Skullcrobat, he can only pendulum clowns), hopefully you've drawn into 2+ Statues, pendulum, then draw Exodia for win. GGEZ. Maybe throw some other shit into the extra deck, idk. Millennium Cross is an alternative to BSs since you clearly can't do both. If that's too bricky, check the side deck. And if you wanna make this deck totally illegal, max out Monkeyboard and throw in Stormwinds.

Oh, and if you don't like BSs, there's Heat Wave in the side deck, along with alternate draw engines. You can cycle Ladyange with Odd-Eyes Seer, but you can't use her draw with Morganite.

Very simple, and straight to the point deck. The deck is a beat down deck with negates to disrupt your opponent. Other cards to consider are things like Dark Bribe for spell/trap negation, Solemn Judgment, and other cards like these. I would conisder it also a autopilot/Bandit Keith deck to a degree.

CUBIC

Unification of the Cubic Lords  and Duza the Meteor Cubic Vessel  are the main cards here , Unification of the Cubic Lords  providing up to 3 extra summons every time a cubic monster leaves the field(That inculdes banishing and returning to hand as well), and Duza the Meteor Cubic Vessel beeing able to search for it and send it to graveyard directly from the deck and beeing able to keep repeat this up to the number of Unification of the Cubic Lords left.

Crimson Nova the Dark Cubic Lord This card is here mainly for the chance to get summoned turn1/2 by revealing 3 cubic cards with different names, it is a powerhouse capable of OTKing, also in the very rare case you have 3 of them and Unification of the Cubic Lords , you can opt for its fusion form.

Cubic Dharma and Cubic Karma serve mainly as alternative search targets for Duza or help fullfill Crimson Nova the Dark Cubic Lord  summoning conditions.

Cubic Causality is a cubic specific targeted permanent effect and attack negate trap that can potentially affect more than 1 target.

Cubic Mandala huge floodgate with many conditions attached to it.

Buster Gundil the Cubic Behemoth and Indiora Doom Volt the Cubic Emperor help search for specific cubic cards and stall for time and mill cards with the help of duza, recommended on slow matchups where you think you can have enough time to find Necro Fusion to get Crimson Nova Trinity the Dark Cubic Lord 

Cubic Wave is mainly here for its graveyard effect which is a one sided permanent effect negation for the entire enemy board if used with enough fuel.

Vijam the Cubic Seed is a 0/0 fiend type monster that synergizes with the Sacred Beasts engine , battle destruction immunity makes it a good stalling tool , and its ability to place cubic counters can be a surprise to plenty.

DANGER

Danger! Nessie!  and Danger! Chupacabra!  help seΝd cards to the garveyard ,where you want them , especialy Unification of the Cubic Lords while also providing bodies for Extra Deck plays.

SACRED BEASTS

Dark Beckoning Beast  and Opening of the Spirit Gates  help summon 0/0 Fiend type monsters to extend your Extra Deck plays while also providing reliable discard engine and able to trade cards for bodies and vise versa with the help of Raviel, Lord of Phantasms - Shimmering Scraper .

STANDALONE CARDS

Absolute King Back Jack is a 0/0 fiend which synergizes with the Sacred Beasts engine and discard synergy while also helping set traps on the enemy turn to avoid spell speed 1 destructions.

Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion is great against other graveyard focused decks , or as a countermeasure for when the oppponent has graveyard hate.

Raigeki Break and Terrors of the Overroot are traps that destroy monsters/spell/traps so they are usefull in any case you need something out of the field, synergize well with Absolute King Back Jack and help trigger Cubic Mandala .

Ferret Flames are great when the enemy has strong monsters that are unable to OTK you, since it non target shuffle back to deck, almost nothing can dodge it.

Ascator, Dawnwalker ,Fire Ant Ascator 

These are here mainly as another way to send specific cards from your hand to the graveyard while also resulting to a generic lv8 synchro monster, Stardust Dragon for destruction protection or Scarlight Red Dragon Archfiend for soft board whipe and burn damage.

EXTRA DECK

Knightmare Cerberus, Knightmare Phoenix, Knightmare Unicorn are generic link monsters with usefull effect with discard costs that synergize with the strategy, also they help climb to your link 4 monsters Borreload Dragon for when you are on the offensive , to break positions,Topologic Zeroboros for a strong board whipe and huge stats late game , can close games on its own if you dodge interaction for one or 2 turns after the board whipe or Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess optimal choice if you either play first to interact with the opponent's first turn, or you expect to face something you need negated soon.

Linkuriboh and Security Dragon are used for link climbing , especialy Linkuriboh can help trigger Unification of the Cubic Lords by using Vijam the Cubic Seed as its material while having Unification of the Cubic Lords in the graveyard.

Decode Talker is a generic link 3 option usefull as a beater , since it can grow decently in power and protect itself , and you can provide constant fuel for its protection with Opening of the Spirit Gates .

Number 106: Giant Hand made with Danger! Chupacabra! and Duza the Meteor Cubic Vessel and Number 65: Djinn Buster made with 2 Dark Beckoning Beast that use their ability to summon each other are generic negate Xyz monsters usually for turn 1 to have interaction available.

Time Thief Redoer is an alternative rank 4 option.

deck_excerpt: Rip 10 from Extra is pretty good.
deck_description:
Your goal is to get Alba Zoa on the field with Dogmatikamatrix to rip at least 8 cards from your opponent's Extra deck. All of your cards work together to draw you into engine or hand traps and end with an endboard of some flavor of Alba Zoa, Quem, Branded in Red and maybe Regained.

Space for handtraps is at a premium so it's your discretion what the most impactful choices are. Veiler and Nib play well with Fusion and Lulu.

Apkallone was originally Psy-Framelord Omega since you could make that theoretically, but Ariel does better what I wanted Omega to do.

Duality is incredible because you will often end with Maximus on board doing nothing and if your opponent can't kill you that turn they will prioritize removal on Maximus, so making them waste something on Maximus only to tribute it away for Dragoons is often the end of the game. Also turns Granguignol into Dragoons and Granguignol can still activate in grave.

So after playing around alot with Goblins, this is the best Version i found.

Every way to put 2 lvl 3's on the board is full combo. Yes Tour guide is also good, but i prefer the other engines that dont need a normal summon.

These Cards in Hand are full combo: terrortop, e-tele, ze amin, ghost ogre, foxy tune, any level 3 monster and kagemucha knight

I chose a crossout package cause its pretty much impossible to play around Nib or through d-shifter. you can replace it with more copies of your prefered

handtraps.

 

the combo is:

1. get 2 3's on the board, no matter how. (if you use the punk cards, you also get one of the punk traps for your endboard via spider).

2. gabonga time searching dugg.

3. detach to special dugg, searching entrance.

4. activate entrance to search mean and special by detaching

5. go into cherubini and dump clatter

6.overlay XYZ armor fortress onto gabonga and search full armored xyz.

7. overlay crystalzero into dark lancer to have 2 mats to detach.

8. use entrance in grave to return clatter to hand.

9. use mean in grave to special, special clatter from hand, special gabonga from grave.

10. go into spright sprint with clatter and cherubini dumping plaguespreader.

11. summon plaguespreader.

12. synchro denglong, fetching 9 pillars.

 

you have the following interactions: 9 pillars countertrap omni. gabonga attach, sprint bounce, resummon clatter + dugg to search follow up and use full armored xyz to go into cicada king(or the rank 3 xyz of your choice), the dark lancer attach, if you opened with punk a backrow negate or pop.

 

you can add chiwen bi'an and herald so denglong floats into another omni.

deck_excerpt: Time Wizard Finds Actual Play In Deck That Crafts Fun!!
deck_description:
BIG THANKS TO MY FRIEND KNELL FOR BRINGING THIS TO LIFE!!!

 

So, you want to play Time Wizard at your locals. However, you don't want to play a gamble deck or a coin toss deck...for very obvious reasons. So, is there any possible way to turn the zero into a hero? Yes, thanks to an incredibly broken card and THE POWER OF WALT DISNEY'S TOMMOROWLAND!!

 

Behold, the greatest thing to ever happen the Time Wizard: A Fusion Card. This magnificent card is the pinnacle of Time Wizard's potential. How? Simple: the material required is Time Wizard and ANY effect monster. So, of course, we are gonna slap Super Polymerization in the deck and laugh all the way to the end of time. Now, your opponents will have PTSD flashbacks of the time their Chengying got turned into the greatest wizard in all of time!

 

So....what else are we doing to support him? Adding Witchcrafters of course! These spellcasters already have wonderful synergy with Time Wizard thanks to their type, and he can be used for most of their cards!! Just grind out your opponents with Witchcrafter effects and spell recycling! Honestly, that's how you'll win 90% of your games, but that ONE GAME where you Super Polymerization with Time Wizard will be the talk of your locals!!! (Yes, we have other actually good Super Poly targets as well, but who cares?)

If you do find that THE MIGHTY TIME WIZARD isn't enough, just side him and super poly out for whatver you need. Or bring in Boarder and Summon Limit and watch EVERYONE HATE YOU!!! Good luck!!!

Basically I spent quite a bit of time Trying to Optmize and Theorycraft this deck,since it was my first deck when I came back to Yugioh in 2016-17(yeah probably not the best idea ever but hey I like Big Numbers) and I have some emotional attachment to it.Overall I had 2 aproachs with this deck one being more Board Break Focused with the Sky Striker Engine,and this more HT Focused Aproach assuming no big meta changes I prefer this one due to the fact that its more balanced towards the go first vrs go second spectrum(Important considering there will be a Better going second deck on the meta).

Basically the entire concept is that you have 12 1/1.5 card OTK Combos(Urgent Schedule,Advance Gearframe and Wyvern) and all your Extenders let then play through certain HTs and interactions, and any combination of 2 Machines Also Threatens similar Lines

For Quick Explanation on some cards:

1-Catapult/Geartown:It feels like it should be run at more Copies I mean both summons from deck and are good combo pieces! But in my experience almost every hand that contained a Naturaly Drawn Copie of either of then Died to 1 single well timed HT, you could argue for 2 Catapult for the Grind Game but you can have other ways to follow up even with 1 Catapult and Grinding isnt what you want to do with AG

2-Dugares:Its a Solid Card that makes it certain hands can play through a Nibiru.

3-Ancient Gear:Dragon : Will Update the deck when its realesed as of now the thing,I want it to be the most is either or both an Extender that summons itsellf from hand or when used as Fusion Material(Extension off AG Fusion)

Pure concept to test out for Ashened. The main concept/ combo of the archtype doesnt utilize its normal summon, with the main normal summon targets being Priestess. Deck has great swarm potential and great board presence with all of its special summons. The incorporation of the Kashtira package is mainly to get bigger bodies on board for OTK's, with the combination of set rotation to get field spells out quickly (Pressured Planet for search or Obsidim to extend).

HFD, Called By The Grave, and Crossout Designator are the first cards to be considered as flex spots depending on match-ups versus Snake-Eys, FK, and back row decks. A budget alternative for the deck would be to swap the 3 Bonfire with Pot of Prosperity as deck is not super reliant on extra dexk but great resource with TY-Phon just being a quick threat and a bunch of removal options that are mostly accessible. Baronne easy access with combonation of ghost girls normal summon + lvl 7/ Effect Veiler normal + Veidos.

Open to suggestions or feedback. One thing to consider is the possibility of dead hands with number of hand traps/ interruptions added as there is not much support for initial Ashened release. Agnimal Candle could be swapped for Droll/Ash Blossom as an easy bonfire search target for free extender and a modular tuner for easy syncro. Chaos Angel could also be viable as Ashened monsters are all dark.

deck_excerpt: Idols and World Destroyers, oh my.
deck_description:
Attempting to follow both Monarch and Live Twin ratios with tweaks made for the deck's goal, the goal is to Tribute Summon during the opponent's turn rather than yours as a going first deck. Though in this day and age where losing the coin flip matters, Forbidden Droplet is played in the main as a precautionary. 

What to expect: A bricky, yet fun idea.

What to do: With draw power like Pantheism and Ki-Sikil, Card Advance is used here as a band-aid for the most indirect usage of Pot of Duality just to nab the card that's within reach. The goal is to get Zaborg the Mega Monarch and Escalation of the Monarchs. If unable, the other Monarchs can do. You'll be setting up a generic Evil Twin board while setting backrow, and if the stars poorly align, you'll pull off Sunny Snitch then activate Escalation of the Monarchs to tribute over the Evil Twins on board to summon Zaborg. The rest is self-explanatory on what you'll be doing with his effect.

What to replace: If you're confident with top decking, you can replace Card Advance with any other staple, like Ash Blossom, Droll & Lock Bird, Effect Veiler, etc. You can also replace some of the other Extra Deck monsters used as Zaborg fodder like N'tss for other Xyz plays or Link plays. 

Why play this deck: Because it's funny when you pull it off.

A best case scenario lab field replay: https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=120995-58110027

Here's my take on big-ship Kozmo. Psychic Processor is the bread and butter, we're essentially playing 6 copies with Emergency Teleport. 

Allure of Darkness to deep draw, Kozmotown to get them back. Stuck with a heavier Dark lineup as opposed to the regular ratios of ships to pilots. 

Only the single Psychic Arsenal since we're already playing three and three of Eclipser and Dark Destroyer, and it makes Dark Planet searchable.

Dark Planet is more of the flex spot, rarely ever summon it but hey it's there- trying to make it work.

Originally I wanted to make a more Psychic based variant but none of them are very good, you'd be better off playing FireKing Kozmo but even then that's bad by todays standards (I haven't tested it with the new Fire King support though)

I basically traded off the usual playstyle of Kozmo Wincan (Tincan) in favour of big ships. 

The deck still OTKs extremely easily, any combination of a single Dark Destroyer + Other Ship or Farmgirl means game if you can connect with Farmgirl once. 

Trap Tracks is MVP of the deck, pop a ship with it and you get the float effect and whatever trap you want. I'm of the opinion that Storm Kings Return is probably the best recursion trap when compared to Back to the Front and the new Emergency Apport trap. Since SKR returns the summoned monster to your hand you can revive something then let it return to your hand and re-summon it with another pilot. 

Extra deck can be whatever you want, was originally testing Extravagance but it conflicted way too much with Kozmotown's mulligan effect.

Card Destruction is there just for digging, would be better in a Psychic variant since you could Soartroopers for Strawman then Strawman for a ship.

Let me know what you think, give it a try. Don't fuss too much about Dark Planet- cut it if you want.

deck_excerpt: Cubic, Charmer, Gizmek, Knightmare, Topologic, Fusion
deck_description:
A very fun deck (and a personal favorite), updated for a more competitive format.

OBJECTIVE: Summon Crimson Nova and burst your opponent, paired with the cubic spells, "Cubic Karma" and "Cubic Wave", that could push Crimson Nova into a 11,200 ATK beast than can splash two attacks and burn for 3000 damage during the End Phase. Also it is unnafected by almost every main monster in the current metagame. It is an auto winner ! ! ! 

MAIN PLAYS:

  • "Duza" is the MVP because it can search any cubic monster (Cubic Karma), become a monster negator (Cubic Wave), a monster recover (Cubic Dharma), a combo starter (Unification), or became a muscle guy via its own effect
  • "Foolish Burial Goods" work the same way as "Duza", so it is usually an starter or even a extender
  • "Vijam" is a good barriage to stall against attacks and a negator. It is also good to start some link plays with "Relinquished Anima" (and trigger an "Unification" from grave to start the combos), or smash a "Super Starslayer TY-PHON" when in trouble
  • "Forbidden Droplet" is very OP in this deck. It can send your Cubic cards to the grave so that you stun your opponent and trigger your combos
  • "Super Polymerization" is nuts, works in the same way as "Forbidden Droplet", allowing you to boardwipe your opponent and begin your combos

SUPPORT PLAYS:

  • "Reasoning" is gold in this deck, because you don't play a lot of monsters and you want your Cubic spells/traps in the graveyard to enable your main plays. The better comes when you can special summon a monster, specially if it is a "Duza", allowing some crazy combos 
  • "Slash Draw" has multiple roles aside from draw power: It can discard a Cubic card; it can send multiple cards from your deck; it can recover your most valuable spells from grave (like "Lightning Storm", "Super Polymerization", "Instant Fusion", "Reasoning", etc.)
  • "Instant Fusion" can be your second "Called by the Grave": Special summon "Millennium-Eyes Restrict" and be protected against hand traps or the disruptions from your opponent's monsters, then you could use it to start your link plays with your other monsters
  • The "Charmers" link monsters are pretty OP , they can be an auto-link 4 summon. Take advantage of your opponent monsters to extend your combos, or to boardwipe the field with a one-card "Topologic Zeroboros" (if you previously had a "Unification" in the graveyard)
  • "Gizmek Taniguku" is a very fun tech that can recycle your "Duza" for the long plays, so, you want it in the graveyard almost all the time 

PROS: 

  • The "surprise" factor allows to smash unaware opponents
  • Unnafected boss monster that can autowin games 
  • A toolbox that can play around into many perilous games
  • This version of the deck boardwipes ! ! ! 

CONS

  • Very susceptible to backrow heavy decks
  • It tends to consume its resources very fast, if you don't win by turn 2 - 4, you're pretty dead 
  • This version of the deck relies on the Extra Deck. Be careful ! ! ! 
  • Adding handtraps or other engines will make you brick
  • You'll need a lot of skill to pilot this deck against resource heavy decks like: Snake-Eyes, Umi decks, Labyrinth, Traptrix, Earthbound
tentando fazer um deck bom e talvez barato

Stun the opponent with various continuous traps until you can summon the powerful Uria, Lord of Searing Flames. Uria gains 1000 attack for each continuous trap in your graveyard and, once per turn, it can destroy 1 face-down spell or trap that the opponent controls without either player responding with a spell or trap of their own. Imperial Custom is key to this strategy because it protects your other continuous traps from battle and card effect destruction. Vortex Trooper, Upstart Goblin, Morphing Jar, and Magic Planter boost consistency by allowing you to draw cards. Vortex Trooper in particular can shuffle 2 dead cards from your hand back into the deck to draw 2 new cards. Finally, Thunder King Rai-Oh supports the deck with its anti-meta effects and strong 1900 attack.

Some Tips

Thanks to Edison format's rules, you can activate Uria, Lord of Searing Flames' effect with priority, allowing it to avoid Bottomless Trap Hole and Torrential Tribute.

Soul Taker beats Jinzo and Machina Fortress.

Breaker the Magical Warrior and Mystical Space Typhoon beats Royal Decree and Dimensional Fissure.

Imperial Iron Wall counters any deck that loves to banish cards.

Royal Oppression can negate Macro Cosmos' activation.

deck_description:
Goodmorning everyone! This is the decklist that I (Antonino from BBT) brought to the last Local. This deck managed to get to the top 16 with a score of 3W-2L-1D.

The deck is designed to go second as Fluffal can't get many disruptions going first (best case Toadally, S:P and an Edge Imp Scythe in the hand and a Dragostapelia in the field if you're lucky, not really a Fluffal endboard)

Instead, thanks to the interruption of Edge Imp Scythe to Frightfur Cruel Whale and the various ways to board clear the deck can manage to OTK. Draw the outs is not a problem as thanks to Toy Vendor, Fluffal Wing and Fluffal Penguin we manage to draw a lot and TTT give us everything we want. The deck also runs Spoly because is a really fun card (when the one using it is you)

deck_description:

Blind second and smash boards with Triple Tactics Thrust, Kaijus, Lightning Storm and more! This deck is also fairly consistent since it several draw cards, and Trade-In can be activated multiple times a turn! 

Games are usually extremely short, it doesn't matter if you win/lose the coinflip since you blind second, and it's very satisfying tearing down your opponent's board!

Either hit for game with 8000+ ATK Gren Maju, or OTK with a 9000 ATK Numeron Dragon! 

I’m not going to publish a long article with card ratios, combos, and strategies for this deck since it’s very straight-forward. Banish your own cards, obliterate your opponent’s board, summon big beatsticks and attack for game!

GLHF Duelists!

Note that many monsters in the Extra Deck don't need to used, you don't have to make the expensive URs for this to work.

You can revive Reptilianne Gardna with Limit Reverse then return Limit Reverse to the hand with Cosmic Fortress Gol'gar's effect to destroy Gardna and search for any Reptilianne monster.  Reptilianne Naga is a tuner that can't be destroyed in battle and can be used as material with Cosmic Fortress Gol'gar to summon Reptilianne Hydra.

deck_name: Tensions in the BRICS bloc: Brazil challenges China and Russia in search of leadership
deck_excerpt: Discover the main events in geopolitics by clicking here!
deck_description:
Brazil is seen as a developing country, seeking partnerships and alliances to strengthen its position on the international stage. Among these alliances, the countries of the BRICS group stood out - Brazil, Russia, India, China and South Africa. Together, these countries sought greater global influence and greater independence in relation to Western countries.

 

Behind the scenes, Brazil began to follow a dangerous path, marked by greed, power and manipulation. The Brazilian leadership saw partnerships with China and Russia as an opportunity to expand its influence and strengthen its economy, but at the same time it saw a threat in being just another member of the BRICS group.

 

With diplomatic skill and strategic coolness, Brazil began to adopt a stance of apparent neutrality, while actually working behind the scenes to undermine the trust of its Chinese and Russian partners. Through subtle manipulations and political articulations, Brazil managed to deceive the world, presenting itself as a country that is an ally of everyone, but in reality seeking only its own benefit.

 

Through privileged information and subtle blackmail, Brazil managed to obtain commercial and political advantages from both the Western and Eastern sides, playing a dangerous and dishonest game. While China and Russia invested time, money and resources in partnerships with Brazil, Brazil took advantage of the situation to strengthen its own position and undermine the confidence of its partners.

 

Brazil will be exposed as a traitor, a manipulator who seeks only its own benefit to the detriment of its allies. The other countries in the BRICS group will feel betrayed and deceived, realizing that Brazil was never a true ally, but rather an unscrupulous opportunist.

 

The lesson that remains is clear: never trust Brazil. Its false neutrality and diplomatic manipulations show that this country is capable of anything to achieve its objectives, even if it means betraying the trust of its partners. It is necessary to be alert and vigilant in a world where loyalty is increasingly rare.

deck_excerpt: Blue-eyes White dragon 2024(unoffical) structure deck x3   v2, no xyz,pendulum,link
deck_description: Blue-eyes White dragon 2024(unoffical) structure deck x3   v2, no xyz,pendulum,link
Fire king deck

My Eternal Favorite

 

Welcome. This is my first time posting here and I'm still figuring things out, hopefully it's not too bad.

I played a lot YuGiOh!-Decks over the course of time and whilst I love many deck themes like Visas Starfrost and everything World Legacy related, also other things like Salamangreats and Marincesses, I can't say I ever fell in love with a deck quite as much as Yubel and her way of doing things.

When I started playing YuGiOh! around 5 years ago again and trying to get into it again, I went trough all the deck themes that there are and Yubel immediately shot into my memories again. I loved her character story back then in GX and her effect is actually quite interesting even tho not really playable. Not even as material for Neos Fusion, as Neos Kluger did not exist back then. Nontheless, I did set up a weired Fireking Version playing Yubel and till this day never actually played it. Which might be better. 

Long story short, after wishing for a Structure Deck for her for a long time, I finally.. Did not get that. But instead, we got tons of very good support and even more to come in the future! But let's keep it at Phantom Knightmare state for now. The version after Legacy of Destruction will come later and should we ever get the fusion monster of her that is currently just a OCG exclusive promo-card, then this will go absolutely Mount Everest.

Anyway, let's begin!

This is my pure version of the deck and revolves all around Yubel and her other versions which I will call "alts" from now on, inflicting reflective battle damage to your opponent and controlling the field. There are currently 5 versions of her:

Yubel - A fiend with 0/0 ATK & DEF, Lvl 10 and the effect that she can't be destroyed by battle, which is the same with all other Yubel-alts. If she's destroyed anywhere by card effect, you can trigger her effect in the graveyard or banish staple and summon her alt #2. If she's attacked by an opponents monster, the opponent gets the damage instead. In your endphase, you must pay a maintenance cost of tributing one monster, or else she's destroyed. This however will not trigger her own floating effect.

Yubel - Terror Incarnate - Her second alt, same stats but Lvl 11 has the same battle protection and no maintenance cost. Instead, she destroys all other monsters on the field during the endphase. If your opponent attacks her, she inflicts burn damage to your opponent just like the normal Yubel. When this face-up card leaves the field, it summons the 3rd alt from anywhere. Unfortunately, it says when and not if- That means it misses a lot of timing. This card must leave the field as the last thing that happens, otherwise it won't trigger. Means, you can't link her away and by that trigger her effect, even one of the new cards does not work with her. Yet.

Yubel - The Ultimate Nightmare - Her third alt and the probably weakest one when it comes to defence. Same stats, Lvl 12 this time. No floating but the ability to destroy a monster that you attack (or that attacks her) after battle and inflict the attack points of said monster as battle damage.

Spirit of Yubel - One of her new alts and probably one of the best cards in the deck. Original statline again and luckily Lvl 10. It summons itself on opponents attack declaration and either adds to your hand or sets it directly from your deck, a spell or trap card that mentions "Yubel". It also floats on destruction from anywhere into the original Yubel. Keep in mind, this floating is not once-per-turn.

Yubel - The Loving Defender Forever - Her for now final alt, the big bad bossmonster and probably the only real "Boss-Monster" this deck even needs. 0/0 ATK & DEF, Lvl 12. A fusion monster that requires one Yubel-alt + X Effect-Monsters on the field. Yes, that means you can use Super Polymerisation to fuse up to 12 monsters on the field. She cannot be destroyed by either card effect or battle and also inflicts burn damage on summon = 500 x the amount of fusion material used for it's summoning. So this burn damage can range from 1000 to 6000. If something attacks her or she attacks something, your opponent receives burn damage after the damage step = the ATK of the opponents monster and right after, the monster is banished.

Now that we know everything about Yubel and her alternative versions, we go over the other new cards.

Samsara D Lotus - A retrain of the original Samsara Lotus (which can also be used in this deck to a certain extend, I guess...?) The D Lotus; to which I will refer as Samsara Lotus from now on) is an extender, starter and control tool, the very first "pseudo-negate" that this deck offers and currently the only one. It's a level 1 fiend with 0/0 ATK & DEF that can be tributed as cost, to special summon a Yubel monster from the deck. Keep in mind, due to their summoning restrictions, this works only on the original Yubel and Spirit of Yubel. Most of the time, you wanna summon the latter with it. In grave it can either special summon itself during the End Phase or get onto your hand, as long as you control the original Yubel. Make sure to trigger Samsara Lotus first and then Yubel, to use it as fodder to keep her alive. It's your End Phase after all, you can decide what triggers first. It's 3rd effect is a pseudo negate, you can tribute it while controlling the original Yubel to make an activated opponents monster's effect become "Destroy one Yubel-monster on the field instead".

Geistgrinder Golem - A retrain of the original Grinder Golem. You either reveal it on your hand together with a Yubel-monster and special summon it to the opponents field, then if the revealed monster was Spirit of Yubel or the original one, you can special summon it to your side of the field. This sets you up for attacking your opponent, even if his field is empty. If the Golem is in your grave, you can also special summon it when the original Yubel is special summoned. On the field, it heals your opponent (talking from your opponents view here) for 3000 LP whenever a Yubel attacks it. Later more to that.

Nightmare Pain - Yubels partner in crime. It's a permanent spell card and throws back all battle damage at your opponent, that you would have from battles with your Yubel-monsters. This applies before Yubels countless effects. Means Yubel, Terror Incarnate, Ultimate Nightmare and Loving Defender will inflict double damage. Attack An opponents 3000 ATK monster with Ultimate Nightmare and your opponent will receive net worth of 6000 damage. It's active effect is that you can destroy a DARK monster in your hand or on your field to add Yubel or a card that mentions her to your hand from your deck, except itself. Keep in mind, the destruction is not a cost. 

Mature Chronicle - A retrain of Spell Chronicle, it's a permanent spell that collects "Chronicle Counters" whenever a monster is special summoned, that is or mentions Yubel, to either side of the field. You can then once per turn remove Chronicle Counters from anywhere on the field to activate one of its effects.

1. - Special summon the original Yubel from your graveyard.

2. - Banish a card from your deck.

3. - Add a banished card to your hand. This works even with cards that are banished face-down. Nice against Cash-tira.

4. - Destroy one card on the field. This does not target.

5. - Add Super Polymerisation to your hand.

Keep in mind, if you control multiple copies of it, you collect counters twice or trice as fast. You can also use the original Spell Chronicle in culmination with it. But do you really want that? The card is not really good. Sorry.

Eternal Favorite - The last new card for now, a permanent trap card that acts either as a revive of Yubel-monsters from the grave or banished staple or as a Super Polymerisation, as long as you control the original Yubel. The latter effect needs you to send it to the graveyard tho as well as a card from the hand. That is a cost, so your opponent can't destroy it to hinder you from fusing, he can however negate it. Then you lost two cards. It's still a very good card and should be in every Yubel based deck. It can even be searched by Elemental HERO Flame Wingman - Infernal Rage 

But more to that later on in another guide, when I come to my E-HERO variant.

 

 

Unofficial Support

 

Now we come to a big part of the Yubel theme. You might have noticed, that theY all share the fiend-type, 0/0 ATK & DEF statline. This opens us a huge door to another seemingly forgotten in-time archetype: Sacred Beasts.

It's time to shine for them and holy cracker, they do. We have a couple of cards here that are a must have in the Yubel line up. Let's go trough them.

Dark Beckoning Beast - A Lvl 2 fiend with the Yubel statline, it searches you Raviel, Uria or Hamon (those are the Sacred Beasts) or whatever card they mention. Those are a lot, but theres really only one that is important in this version of Yubel. It also let's us do a second normal summon on a fiend with 0/0 ATK & DEF, so it works well with either itself or with the new Samsara Lotus.

Opening of the Spirit Gates - A permanent spell card that is not an attraction in some adventure park. On activation, it searches us one of the Sacred Beasts or one monster that mentions them from your deck to your hand. It then remains on the field and can revive us any fiend with the Yubel statline, the cost is discarding one card. You do not declare a target here before you actually do the revive. Instead, you must have a valid target on activation in the graveyard, so it won't work with an empty GY. However, it will work to discard the same card you are going to revive. The third effect lets you add a permanent spell to your hand from your GY, as long as you control at least one Lvl 10 monster. It's nice for keeping up your recourses if your opponent for example destroys your Nightmare Pain.

The Unchained Engine

 

People love the Unchained-Engine in this deck. And so do I. People play different versions of it. I came up with the one that fits me the most and that I like the most. The following cards I chose to play here.

Unchained Soul of Sharvara - It summons itself easily by destroying a set card or a fiend (for example Yubel) and searches us an Unchained- spell or trap by setting it from the deck to the field.

Unchained Soul Lord of Yama - It summons itself from just 2 of our fiend monsters and searches Sharvara. In the grave, it can revive any fiend monster if a card we control is destroyed.

Unchained Soul of Rage - A good going first option, in case our opponent for some reason forces us to do so..? During your opponents main phase, it serves as a Quick-Link-Summon with a special summoned monster our opponent controls, into a DARK link monster. Alternatively, on destruction it adds us a fiend from our GY to our hand. Good to recover the likes like Spirit of Yubel.

Unchained Soul of Anguish - A good target for Rage's primary effect. Also adds us a fiend from the GY to our hand uppon destruction. Good for keeping up our resources for a longer grind game.

Abominable Chamber of the Unchained - The trap we search with Sharvara. It revives one of our Unchained monsters. Most of the time, you'll be reviving Soul of Rage with this either after it got destroyed and you used the recovery effect or after you used it as Link-Material. You can use both of the effects in the same turn that way.

How to play

 

I play a pure going 2nd variant and I firmly believe that as of now, that is the best of all ways. When the new support comes out with Legacy of Destruction, this might shift for but now, the going second variant is my way to go. So I play a ton of board breakers.

Nibiru, the Primal Being is our only handtrap in the main deck. Trust me, we won't need more. We play 3x Radian, the Multidimensional Kaiju as well as 2x Lava Golem and these boys crack up our opponents board like nothing else. You can also play other Kaijus for more damage, but Radian is by far the best, as he is DARK and works with Nightmare Pain. If we do not draw into any of those, we also have 3x Forbidden Droplet which is still one of the best going-second tools in the entire game in my eyes, as well as 3x Super Polymerization. 

By all means, this is a "Unga-Bunga" deck with a little added tech but I still also would not call it easy. The basic procedure is straight forward and very "Head-trough-wall", brute forcing our way trough boards. It might also happen, that we give the opponent a Kaiju and then proceed to pass and go into Endface. Just to let them activate our Spirit of Yubel in hand.

As for our important tech-cards, we have the likes like Piri Reis Map, One for One and Monster Reborn for additional summons and Pot of Prosperity as well as Triple Tactics Talent for additonal draw power. Be careful with the pot, as it halves the damage you deal for the rest of the turn. The deck is very grind heavy tho, so it's not that big of a problem.

Things to be aware off, before I get to the Combos and tech's.

Piri Reis Map and Lava Golem bite each other. If you used Piri-Reis-Map, you technically cannot use Lava Golem in the same turn, as Piri Map kills the card you searched with it, if you don't normal summon it. It also halfes your Life Points, luckily only after it successfully resolved but still. This did cost me one or another duels/matches in the past.

The deck is currently only really hard countered by Kashtira, even against Snake-Eyes it has a fairly easy time, if played well. Banishing the cards face-down is a hard counter however. If they are banished face up, they can still be used as the Yubel's summon themselves even from the banished staple.

Runick and any variants of it are a nightmare for this deck but not unplayable. Use your side deck wisely and you'll be able to get over it relatively easy, even if it might only be trough time-out.

Time-out can break your neck with this deck, as I have not found a 100% reliable way to do burn-damage or heal yourself in turn one. Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max is kind of the only way this deck can do either of it but unfortunately, that is not a one-card-combo.

Combos and Techs

 

Basic combos:

 

Normal summon Samsara D Lotus, use it's effect to special summon Spirit of Yubel from your deck to set/add Nightmare Pain to your field/hand. Destroy Spirit of Yubel with Nightmare Pain and add Eternal Favorite to your hand. Spirit of Yubel triggers and summons Yubel. 

Normal summon Dark Beckoning Beast, add Opening of the Spirit Gates to your hand. Activate Opening to add another Beast to your hand. Normal summon the 2nd Beast and Link summon Unchained Soul Lord of Yama to proceed with the Unchained combo line.

 

 

Basic Techs and Tricks:

♦ Link off a single Dark Beckoning Beast into Salamangreat Almiraj to get your Opening of the Spirit Gates revive going

♦ Use Nightmare Pain or other copies of itself as discard fodder for Opening of the Spirit Gates and add them back to your hand with its own effect

♦ As long as you got a possible target in your GY, you can discard the card you going to summon from the GY via Opening of the Spirit Gates, this let's you technically summon fiends from your hand

♦ Discard Geistgrinder Golem and special Yubel back from your GY to immediately summon Geistgrinder Golem, if theres no other Yubel-monster in your hand

♦ Use "already used" copies of card's like Kaiju's, Permanent Spells, etc. as well as Yubel - Terror Incarnate and Yubel - The Ultimate Nightmare  as fodder for your Forbidden Droplet 

♦ Use (multiple copies of) Radian, the Multidimensional Kaiju and bricks like Yubel - Terror Incarnate and Yubel - The Ultimate Nightmare as fodder for Nightmare Pain 

♦ Spirit of Yubel's floating effect is not a once-per-turn

♦ All of Yubel's alts evolve from anywhere. It doesn't matter if they get destroyed and go to the GY or the banished staple, in case something like Dimension Shifter is active.

♦ All of Yubel's alts can be evolved into from anywhere, except the banished face-down pile. It doesn't matter if they are in the hand, deck, GY or banished pile.

♦ 2 Yubel-monsters + Nightmare Pain + a opponents monster with 3000 ATK or more is enough to one-shot your opponent. Attack with both Yubels first, then XYZ-Summon into Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max and deal 2000 burn damage with it's effect.

♦ A Yubel-monster that has it's effects negated, still does deflect damage via Nightmare Pain. It's just that you will receive the damage as well then and your Yubel-monster will be destroyed by that battle. A Spirit of Yubel will then even float into Yubel and you can attack for even more damage.

♦ Eternal Favorite lets you summon Spirit of Yubel but if summoned this way, Spirit of Yubel cannot activate it's search effect, since Eternal Favorite states that neither player can activate effects when that monster is summoned.

Advanced Combos and plays

 

The advanced combos mostly regard the Unchained combos, as the Unchained engine is what really brings the technicality into this deck.

As soon as you have your Unchained Soul Lord of Yama out, you add to your hand Unchained Soul of Sharvara. You then either destroy a set spell/trap you control or a fiend you control to special summon it. Link summon it away toghether with Yama into Unchained Soul of Rage. This sets you Abominable Chamber of the Unchained directly from your deck. You now have a revive set up in your GY in form of Yama which triggers if a card on your field is destroyed. This includes Nightmare Pain in case you still have that left. You can destroy your Soul of Rage to search something with Nightmare Pain and also by that, trigger Rage's effect to add a fiend from your GY and also immediately summon Soul of Rage back trough Yama.

If you do not have Nightmare Pain available, you just leave your Soul of Rage on your field. You'll be able to use it either as a way to go into another DARK Link monster, using your opponents special summoned monster during their Main Phase or in case it get's destroyed, you can do the first combo, just without Nightmare Pain. It is then revivable to still use it's Link-Summon effect via your trap card. Lord Yama should remain in the GY in this case, as it's better to use him to revive Spirit of Yubel for example, in case you don't have one in your hand.

♦ Unchained Soul of Anguish give you an even stronger grind, as it shares the recovery from GY effect with Unchained Soul of Rage 

♦ Knightmare Unicorn is good interruption. Here you can (and actually should...) put in S:P Little Knight instead. I however do not feel it's needed since Nightmare Unicorn is the rarest monster you go into. And do you really wanna pay more than 100,00 € for that..?

♦ Barricadeborg Blocker lets you fend off destruction effects towards your backrow which can be nasty in this deck. It also let's you recover your permanent spells. Keep in mind, it works like Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon and Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer, in that you pay the cost of discarding a card and then tell your opponent, that you will add a card to your hand during the End Phase. If your opponent does not negate that, he won't be able to later on when the recovery actually happens.

♦ Dharc searches you every monster in your deck, except Radian, the Multidimensional Kaiju, Lava Gollum, Nibiru, the Primal Being and Unchained Soul of Sharvara 

Side Decking and other thoughts towards the Meta

 

Side decking is quite easy with this one. It's a pure going-2nd-deck and we are in a constant going-1st meta. You will have no hard time getting what you want there, you either win the coinflip and choose 2nd or lose it and your opponnent will choose you going 2nd. I still think a well thought and meta-optimized Side Deck is crucial.

Here are my thoughts:

♦ Dimension Shifter: This deck is not untoucheable by Shifter. This card is will still cripple you significantly if you're not prepared. If you are prepared tho, you can decide rather to use it or not. Shifter is a instawin card against most decks, so I think it has it's deserved spot here. Just remember siding Forbidden Droplet out. While Shifter is active, Forbidden Droplet cannot be activated.

♦ Drool & Cock Bird: I do 100% believe that Droll is the best handtrap at the moment. This deck is my only deck that does not play it in the Main Deck. If you think your opponent goes to crazy with something like Mannadium or Snake Eyes, side Droll in. This card is a killer if used correctly, like Shifter.

♦ Anti-Spell Fragrance: A neck snap for Runick. I do not like Runick for multiple reasons, be it playing against it or the whole premise behind it. I also said before, this deck struggles only against Kashtira and Runick. Against Kashtira not so much, but Runick is difficult. That's why I like to counter it.

♦ Infinite Impermanence: Very good handtrap. Lovely against decks that "put everything in their normal summon". Can be switched out with backrow hate like Cosmic Cyclone tho, if you dislike Runick as much as I do.

♦ Summon Limit: You do not need many summons in this deck, your key summon (Spirit of Yubel) can be done during your opponents turn, so ... It won me one or another games.

What are this decks weaknesses?

As any other deck, this deck has weaknesses. I'm not TeamShinobi and tell you that it's tHe nEw tIeR zErO dEcK. I mentioned Kashtira earlier, due to them banishing face-down. This can break your neck. Not always, but sometimes. Until we have the fieldspell Nightmare Throne, Kashtira will still remain a threat. Mostly due to it Main Decking D-Shifter. This one makes you unable to use Forbidden Droplet. The deck can also be fairly open to hand-rip effects. If your opponent takes away your keycard before you can use it, then that might be problematic. I look at things like Voiceless Voice and Chimera.

What are this decks strengths?

First of all, you have a ton of "problem solvers". Cards that you put on the field and the opponent simply cannot do anything against it. Examples are your Kaiju's and your Lava Golems, Forbidden Droplet as well as Super Polymerisation. Another big strength is that the deck plays pretty well trough before mentioned insta-win cards like Shifter and Droll. Your GY is not nessecarily needed, often you can also just pass your turn. Most (Omni)negates negate and then destroy ythe card after. Means, if you attempt to guard yourself with Spirit of Yubel but your opponent negates it's activation with for example Baronne de Fleur, it will still get destroyed afterwards and float into Yubel, giving you time to try another turn, with Shifter now gone. Droll is fairly easy to play around as well as you often set cards instead of adding them to your hand.

The probably biggest threat currently is "Snake-Eye". This deck does not have too many problems against the Snakes. You have good Super Polymerisation targets with Mudragon of the Swamp and Garura, Wings of Resonant Life. The biggest threat in that is probably, most of the time S:P Little Knight, but even against that I was able to play around fairly easily. Summon Limit, Shifter and Droll also kill Snake Eyes. So don't worry.

 

Options and evolution

 

This deck is still evolving and I don't think it is perfected yet. Not talking about the new support that comes in a few weeks yet, there might be some other techs and strategies I haven't discovered yet. So heres just a little list to see what options we have and what came to my mind over all the weeks.

♦ Mature Chronicle: The use of this card is kind of a hit or miss. A win-more card. For it's full potential, you search Super Polymerization with it. Currently tho, it's kinda hard to get to 5 Chronicle Counters, except if you hard-draw it and also have an absolutely optimal hand. So currently, you really use it more as an extender for the Yubel revive.

♦ Spell Chronicle: Crazy cool card actually, in combination with Mature Chronicle, it can theoretically search you every card in your deck and generate more Chronicle Counters, however it itself is not searchable and kinda clunky.

♦ Samsara Lotus: I said it already, it kinda works in this deck. You can even get it out with One for One. However, it only works if you don't control open spells or traps. In other words, your most important card, Nightmare Pain.

♦ Chain Material: Such an interesting and cool card. It lets you summon Yubel - The Loving Defender Forever by using up to 13 materials and deal 6500 burn damage. You also do not need a Yubel-monster on your field. Might be a fun tech-option? It might be able to bamboozle an unknowing opponent.

♦ Crossout Designator: You could play that.. I guess? I don't like this card for many reasons but you do you. Make sure to put some more meta staples in your Side Deck or Main Deck then.

♦ Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring as well as the other Yokai-girls. They are good handtraps. No need to say anything more than that, right?

♦ S:P Little Knight: I said it already, it's a very good card. For this deck however, not good enough to justify paying more than a hundred bucks for it in my eyes.

♦ Skill Drain: Fun if you want to kill your opponent and yourself. Lul.

♦ Unchained Soul of Shyama & D/D/D Wave High King Caesar: To go into Caesar with with both your Unchained Souls is cool. I have no clue how that combo works tho.

♦ Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis: Shouldn't be too bad in this deck, but I think it's massively overrated.

♦ Number 35: Ravenous Tarantula: It's like a really weired version of Masquerade the Blazing Dragon for this deck. However, theoretically, your opponent can get over it by simply normal summoning anything with more than 0 ATK and kill it before it does anything. The only way you will use Life Points turn 1 is Piri Reis Map. So not often. Still a nice thought I think.

Thank you for reading

 

If you made it till this point, thank you very much. I hope you enjoyed my little guide and maybe even learned something.

deck_excerpt: Kozmo, Horus, Control, OTK potential, Handfixing
deck_description:
Seen the list for Light and Darkness dragon Horus and adapted it to be Horus Kozmo.

Deck can OTK out of nowhere. Your opponent is forced to start dealing with the Horus cards or lose by getting OTK'd, but with the Kozmo cards you can OTK off a Ship+Farmgirl.

Soartroopers is the MVP of the Kozmo lineup, pitch a pilot for Kings Sarcophagus and revive it with soartroopers. The deck isn't focused as much on floating your ships and more or less you only want to get one of them banished/destroyed to return with Kozmotown then keep fuelling Kings Sarcophagus. 

Zombie Vampire can set up Kozmos in the same way, if you have a ship heavy hand you can either make ZV and revive a pilot to tag into, or if you mill multiple pilots you can Soartroopers them back. 

It's... an interesting deck. Needs a lot further testing. If you don't want to play Summon Limit and TCBOO you can cut all of them and play 3 Trap Tracks to pop a ship or a useless horus main-deck monster and Eradicator Epidemic tributing off Dark Horus/Ship/ZV etc.

deck_excerpt: A twist on Diva Zombies in Edison Format, employing Instant Fusion.
deck_description:
This list runs close to that of my InstaTeleZombies deck, incorporating Deep Sea Diva in place of the Emergency Teleport package.

Diva, after all, can serve as a monstrous extender especially with Instant Fusion at the helm. I'm not sure if this is necessarily better than the other Zombie list, though, given cards like Krebons and Psychic Commander have utility even if you dead draw them. On the contrary, drawing a second Diva is akin to drawing a Garnet. Even still, it is interesting to play around with as both Zombie variants have their strengths. 

I've also been considering playing around with other card in this deck such as Il Blud, a third Diva alongside Spined Gillman (which would allow easy access to Mist Wurm as you'd only need to have a level four monster - something easily accomplishable with Instant Fusion and Darkfire Dragon - at the ready and a Diva in hand to bring it out), and so forth but feel this might be the most consistent list at the moment.

Nevertheless, more testing is needed for both this and the other deck utilizing the Emergency Teleport package. 

I've also made the choice to cut Doomkaiser for Thought Ruler as the latter seems to be more useful more often. The deck pays a lot of life points, after all, which Thought Ruler aids in restoring but that plays second fiddle to the fact that Thought Ruler can aid in allowing you to go on the offensive or even close out games without fear of Dimensional Prison, which I believe is the most common battle trap in the format, and the like.

While Doomkaiser dominates against another Zombie deck, I feel that's akin to switching out Darkfire for Karbonala Warrior to premptively prepare for Koaki Meiru Drago which is commonly used in Dragon lists.  Perhaps I should consider placing Extra Deck monsters in the Side Deck, after all, but that's an idea for another time.

deck_excerpt: Infernoble doesn't miss out on the benefits of the "Fire Format!"
deck_description:
Infernoble is another less known and less played "Fire Format" powerhouse! Relinquished deck

This Deck is really fun and surprisingly competent. Nobody really knows what it does and it is hard for your opponent to intuit.

The gameplan is to out grind the opponent and go for lethal in turns 2 to 4. Often, the game comes to a halt, and you go to time A LOT. But with red resonator and Joyous Melffys you are more than prepared to handle that.

If you have the money, change the Knightmare Unicorn for a second S:P.

Droll and Shifter only damage this deck a little bit. Shifter hurts the grind game and Droll stops you from adding cards on your opponent's turn. I recommend to only side them in in match-ups, where they pretty much oneshot the opponent's deck.

The bane of this deck are stun and burn "strategies". I haven't found a good and reliable answer yet. Just tell yourself that stun players have already failed in life and immediately feel better.

deck_excerpt: Edison Format: Divine Grace Northwemko utilizing Djinn's
deck_description:
Divine Grace Northwemko deck with Lightsworn Engine to fill the GY with Djinn, hoping to resolve Northwemko with Djinn Releaser and Disserere to prevent the opponent from Special Summoning and to be unaffected by Trap cards.
Endymion can become quite indestructible with a few counters on it, allowing Northwemko to 'attach' to it and become near indestructible herself.

Side deck is a WIP but mostly need cards to prevent her from getting Stolen/Swapped or Bounced. 

(For some reason Djinn Releaser isn't marked as Edison legal in the deck builder, despite showing up as legal in the search function, and being released in 2009, so it definitely is. So this Edison Format deck has had to be listed under Non-Meta for now).
